\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid4940319 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Could you tell me then what your father's job was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Yes, 
he was a chargehand - at a boilermakers, and he worked in Shalers dockyard. Actually he worked there the whole of his life, his working life I think. I'm not quite sure about this but I think so. And he - eventually reached the - stage of being a chargeha
n
d. I'm going back now to my earliest recollections when - yes, about 97, 1897, before you were thought of - and - when I sometimes used to take his dinner down to him. If he was working on a special job and they had to work overtime, he would have to stay
 
at work during the dinner hour and - usually the sons and daughters of the workmen - used to take their dinners down, in a red handkerchief. Slopped all the way down because it had gravy in them, but - we used to stand outside the dockyard gates, and - wh
e
n the policeman put his hand up we could all go in. So - we used to go in and find our fathers or our parents, and - they sat down and ate their - their dinners, and off we tootled again. Well he was then - a chargehand of boilermakers. I can't remember m
uch - before that period.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
He came from Queenborough. I'm talking now about Sheerness dockyard by the way which is just opposite. Yes, he came from Queenborough, and - I remember him telling me many - many many years afterw
ard, when I was also working in the dockyard, and I complained to him one day, I said, I couldn't catch a bus - a tram to work, we used to have electric trams. He said, well, what about it? I said, well I was late. He said, well it serves you right. He sa
i
d, when I was a boy I worked a four - I walked four miles to work and - work and four miles back, and so he did. As a lad he was in - living in Queenborough and working in Sheerness you see. And the only means of locomotion - was to walk, which he did. An
d - I also understand from my mother that he did this for many years after they were married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was he apprenticed as a boilermaker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. There were no apprentices in that day, not - from what we would term apprentices. He - apparently got a job in the dockyard, and they sort of - drifting in - in - into doing boilermaking work. That's all there was about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So he worked his way up from being a boy in the dockyard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mm. Yes, that's right. No, I think the - examinations for entry into the d
ockyard - I wouldn't say when - because I think that - quite a number of my elder brothers sat the examination, only one passed, that was my brother a little older than me, about five years older. Then he passed. Now he entered the dockyard - about 188 - 
99. So they were - existing then. I went in in 19 - 04. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did your mother have a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No, my mother had a full time job bringing in children. When - when you have a family of eleven - it's jolly hard work. She had to bring up a family - and -
 on very very inadequate wages incidentally, very very low. No holidays, I can't remember my father having a holiday. That's a blow isn't it. No, I can never remember him having a holiday. And when he at last retired - when I was an apprentice - I always 
s
aid to my other brothers that the shock was so great he died, well he did. He died within a year. But I do think there was something in that argument though, I think that he was - attuned to so much - regularity in his life - that when he lost that - he s
ort of lost the urge to exist, put it that way. That's what I feel about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 He retired from the dockyard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
He retired from the dockyard - when I was an apprentice about the third year of apprenticeship, I should think - about 1907. And - within a year he was dead anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Before she was married your mother didn't work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. Oh - wait a minute. I'm not quite sure about this. But I've got an idea she was a servant. I did hear some sort of story when I was very young - of her working for the
 vicar - of a church in - Queenborough. Now I wouldn't like to say that's authentic, but I think it is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 She came from Queenborough too did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
She came from Queenborough as well, her father - it's going back a bit isn't it I believe that he was
 the - Chief Constable of Queenborough. It sounds a very very high position. But - if you know Queenborough as I knew it when - as a boy it - it only consisted of about one road actually. Incidentally my father was Freeman of Queenborough you know. Mm. I 
think he inherited that. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What advantages did that bring?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh none at all. Well these posts don't mean much do they. I think they're supposed to - in theory - be the reward say of services rendered I should imagine anyhow to the community. But 
- I don't think there's much value in them anyhow. And that applies to today, I think they're all tripe. It's like making an alderman.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did your father belong to a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Yes. I don't know what but I think it was a boilermakers union. Now 
I - I only discovered this after his death by the way. My eldest brother - was looking through his papers. And he said to me - one day, look, this is something to interest you. And this was a copy of a letter that my father had wrote - to a - what they te
r
m the Lords of the Admiralty. In connection with some - application for an increase in wages - that the people in - Sheerness Dockyard were making. And - I remember - it very very plainly because my father signed himself, your very obedient servant - so a
n
d so and so and so you know. And I remember as a kid I thought to myself, well that sounds a weird sort of - sort of address but of course it's fairly typical. But - I don't know much about that side of his - activity. As a matter of face he was very reti
c
ent about that. I don't know why, but he was very reticent. But that might account - this - this might account for it really, that when he died I was only about - sixteen, and I suppose he thought that I wasn't - really mentally alert or fit - to - the co
n
fidences that he could have given me you see. It was a big loss to me actual. But I should imagine probably that that was the reason. Because we were just - before his death we were just sort - going for a walk in the evening, and - having a little chat, 
mostly about football by the way. But we were sort of getting down to a bais, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did he talk about politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
He was a Liberal, which incidentally was fairly revolutionary. Oh yes. In Sheenness it was very revolutionary, I can tell yo
u that. By God it was, mm. I remember an uncle of mine - Uncle Jack, whom I liked immensely - he in a - as a reward for his political activities, had his house, which owned incidentally painted in the Tory colours during an election. Which wasn't very goo
d. Mm. Yes, in the night he got up, he found the walls on the outside of his house all sprawled with - a very vivid blue.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was your father active then in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. My mother would be more active than my father. My mother was - I should say she
 was very fluent. She was quite a good actress in a way - you know, the dialogues and things like that and these little concerts. No, father was very - quiet, self effacing, but - he knew what he thought, and he was able to express it very well, but unles
s you asked him - there would be no expression.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Do you know why he was a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No, I don't know that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 He didn't explain why he supported the party?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. No, we had - as I say, we had no - discussion with him on that thing. With 
my mother, many many years afterwards - it couldn't have been so long after that anyhow, must have been somewhere about 1909 - when I was about nineteen or eighteen, and I joined the Socialist party, and I remember that shook her. And I remember then sayi
n
g to her, well - you're a Liberal and most of Sheerness is Conservative, what does it matter. I can also remember her doing this for me which I thought a lot of - we used to hold open air meetings of course in Sheerness and they were outside a Conservativ
e
 Club. Which - was quite good. But anyhow - it was a normal sort of meeting, none of us would speak really - but we were very enthusiastic, and we had - a scheme of - taking it in turns in taking the chair. Taking it in turns in opening the - meeting etce
t
era, and all doing our bit, and also taking the collection. And I remember one night, I happened to be taking the collection, and there were only about two in the audience, and - somebody put their arm round the back of me and put a penny in the box that 
I had. And I turned round, it was so unexpected you see, I turned round, it was my mother. I said, good heavens. She said, yes, I thought I ought to, she said, you look so lonely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 But she was an active Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Yes. She belonged to the Liberal Gu
ild and all that sort of thing. Yes, oh yes, she was quite enthusiastic, very enthusiastic. The first election I remember - was 1906 I think. That I believe, I'm not quite sure about this, I think that - the - the Liberal party got back into power in 1906
 
didn't they, I think so. Mm. We didn't get back into power, yes we did. Oh Lord yes. A bloke named Doctor Napier - came down, nobody knew anything about him but he came down - and there was a wave - of enthusiasm for the Liberal party, and I remember that
 - Chinese Labour was one of the planks - and - I believe that - at that time there was a lot of Chinese - industrial competition, in England, and for some }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 w}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 eird sort of reason - the Liberal party thought that - the country was going to be overwhelmed with 
Chinamen. But - and I do remember that that was the cry at election. But anyhow the Liberals got back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How did you become a Socialist yourself then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Well I think there was a gradual process. But I can remember - the day when - I felt more indign
ant with the - Tory party than any time in my life. You must remember that - in the workshop in those days things were very - they were very callous. Although we had trade unions, there were very very few who belonged. They were too scared. And the - what
 
shall I say, the bosses - that includes a foreman - of course when - the workmen were made chargehand they thought they belonged to the other class. That sounds very weird but it is true. And - they treated you accordingly. But anyhow I can remember - whe
n
 I was about - seventeen or eighteen I was working with a man for whom I had a very great regard. His name was John Morley. He would be about thirty at that time. He had a wife and two children, two little girls, lovely little girls. And he - I worked wit
h him - and he did a lot of me so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
far that - on Sundays his wife would invite me to their place to tea you see. And sort of the humanising effect it had upon me - as a sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 rapscallion}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  and - it came the period one year - when they were going to give us d
ischarge, and - these rumours used to get about like what they term political leaks today, they were purposely let out. And - everybody knew - that about forty men in the fitting shop were going to be - discharged. And of course that was meant - to put ev
e
rybody on their toes. And I can tell - tell you this it was a most terrible thing in the whole of my experience. Grown men, good mechanics - good craftsmen - scared stiff of their being unemployed. I'm going back now in the days - when there was no unempl
o
yment benefit, you just went out like that, and - the unemployment figures were always very high, and if you got into employment you were damned lucky. But anyhow I remember one day - on the Friday afternoon - when the clerk was coming round giving out th
e
se - papers - everyone was looking you know sort of keeping an eye, here he comes, you know, keep - sort of keep an eye and - on the bloke who was coming along with a - notices, and - he stopped at our bench. And he gave - said, here you are, I can rememb
e
r his tone, I remember the tone that he said it. And - my friend, John Morley took it, he put it in his pocket. And I thought to myself, my God. And I immediately said to him, sorry, John. And he burst into tears. And that shut me up, I thought, God Almig
h
ty, there's a man, a grown man - a fine man in every respect burst into tears. And I think really that I decided there was something wrong politically. And I probably - did the obvious, I joined the Comm - the - Socialist party. Incidentally I have been a
 member ever since. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Which party was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh - going back to the Social party in those days there were - Socialist party Great }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 Britain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 , Independent Labour Party - Socialist Democratic Party, and the British Socialist Party. Now - all the
se parties had to - claim or make claim to about half a dozen men. Because there was very very few of us anyhow. But the particular party that I joined was the British Socialist party, merely because I think of the term British I thought myself this stand
s for all the others - and can swallow the others up, which incident - incidentally they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Which branch did you belong to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Sheerness branch. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 And how many members were there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh - we limited our members - membership in those days to ten. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Why was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Well, what we felt about it, mind you we were all very immature, and we - we were all very enthusiastic, but we did feel was this, that the only members we wanted were people who - had enthusiasm. We didn't 
want people - sort of paying members. We wanted people who were prepared to work, and we decided that there would be only about ten people - who would be prepared to work - so we limited the number to ten. Now that - had rather a peculiar effect. As soon 
a
s we knew that - broadcast that we were going to have no members above ten, we had a lot of members - people who wanted to join. But anyhow - we did limit it to that extent, and we also - decided this. That everybody had to be prepared - to speak. Whether
 they could speak or not didn't matter, they had to be prepared to get at any open air meeting you had and - oh and hold the platform. Incidentally it often wanted holding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Where would the meetings be, in the market place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. At - I don't know whether you know Sheerness do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I haven't been there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Well you haven't missed much. Anyhow I suppose probably - the best building in Sheerness in those days was the Conservative Club. It was quite a good building. Now opposite the Conservative
 Club - was an opening about - length of our garden leading down to a school, which was a National school, which - where incidentally my wife, who married me, taught. I was her only failure as a pupil. But anyhow that's where we used to hold our meetings,
 so that the platform which we used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 build up}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  with }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 tumble}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
 - thumbscrews and that sort of thing, we built up and face the Conservative - Club entrance. It was good fun too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was that Saturday nights?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I'm not sure about Saturday nights, I don't th
ink it was. Because mainly because we were otherwise engaged. But often on a Saturday, we would go - to a village - on the other side of the island, near Sittingbourne, Chennon, any places like that, and we'd go out to a little village pub, and we'd have 
a
 drink, and we used to ask the - landlord whether he would mind if whether we had a meeting outside of his door, and - usually they used to say no, that's all right. And we used to borrow one of his - lemonade boxes - for a platform, and just - have a go.
 
For about half an hour, that was all there was bout it, asking questions, hoping there were none, and - then go back and have a yarn with the people inside and - that was all there was about it. And I used to thoroughly enjoy that you know. I think most o
f
 our chaps did. We did have a stunt after a time, of always opening our meetings with a - a song. And - incidentally we had - there were four of us - and we had a damned good quartet. Oh there wasn't any doubt about that. And we used to sing either the In
ternational, Red Flag or something like that to open up. Which was also rather good fun.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Those would be agricultural labourers you were talking to mainly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes. I would say yes. There was - there was - nothing - nothing industrial in the neighbourhood. Nothing industrial at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How did they take to Socialism then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Well I don't know whether they understood it. After all we were not very articulate. But - I think after a time - they used to enjoy it. It's always enjoyable to see other pe
ople make fools of themselves anyhow isn't it, and there they had - say half a dozen of us or so - who were trying to do what they obviously couldn't do. I think they enjoyed it. Anyhow we used to treat them with a pint, treat them to a pint or two.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How much regular support did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How much what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How much regular support did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
There were one or two pubs - I was trying to think of the name - of the village near Tennon, I forget what the name of the village was, but I do kn
ow there that - the publican was very anxious for us to go, and also on one occasion when we were outside saying goodbye one of them said, well come again won't you. I think probably they took it in the light in which we meant it. We were having a good bi
t
 of fun, and incidentally if we were doing any good - that was incidental. And I think they were having their bit of fun too. I think we learnt more off them than they learnt off us. I mean it - to me it was very instructive. I'd never dealt with farm lab
ourers before. And my God - those fellows, they were jolly fine chaps. And what were their wage, fourteen bob a week. Some of them less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you have meetings in the winter, indoor meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes. Oh yes, indoor meetings. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Discussions and talks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Not discussions so much. Discussion for - for - private consumption. But we used to hold - about three meetings a year on Sunday evening, in what is a - Wellington Hall, that was at the back of a pub, and it was quite a nice hall, we used t
o hold our meetings there, we used to get a speaker - speaker down from the headquarters - who I think enjoyed himself, and - that was all there was about it. We never got much of an audience. But - frankly we were not - very concerned about audiences. We
 
were certainly more concerned - about ourselves. Very egotistic weren't we. But - that was all there was about it, we - looked forward to these meetings, we all wanted to have a go, and - and whether the people in - the audience understood what we were ta
lking about - didn't matter a lot to us. I can remember one Sunday night - having a go at Churchill. Most awful cheek. But anyhow, Churchill at that time - was - Home Secretary. And at that ti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 me there was a fair amount of hooliganism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, probably not as much as there is now though, and - they were after some criminal, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Sidney Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I don't know whether you know the history of it, do you? Well anyhow, I remember - getting very sarcastic - sarcastic about Churchill - paying more - concern - to the -
 criminals of Sidney Street than he was to the - farm labourers and engineers in the - workshops and that sort of tripe, which of course looking back was - pretty absurd.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What were the books you read about Socialism?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What were the books? Oh Lord. I suppose Karl Marx was the awful thing.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You read Karl Marx?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes, I did study Karl Marx, and - Kortsky, what was his name Kortsky, yes. Oh there was quite a number of books that I had. I also - became an outdoor student of - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}Ruskin{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. From which I transferred to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Central{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Labour{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, all correspondence mind you. I mean it's all right to talk about going to college and all that sort of thing - and you could get to Ruskin College fairly cheaply - but the - the - compe
tition to go to Ruskin College - as a paid student - was terrific you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 That would be before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh my God, yes. Oh yes. Mm. Oh yes, I was - I'm not sure about the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Central{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Labour{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 when they first - sprung up. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 About 1912 I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Was it? I thought it was - older than that, but anyhow about that time, but anyhow I - I know I was one of their first students. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What did you study there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Logic. Which a lot of my friends used to laugh at. E
conomics and Industrial History. And I - I learnt quite a lot really. Most of which I forgot afterwards, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did anyone else in the branch join the college?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. No. No, I was rather pleased about that, I could tell them a lot. No, I was a member of - I was a - correspondence student and then was - during the war I would say up to about 1916. I would think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Can you tell us about how you started work yourself, did you start work when you were at school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No, no, except in
 a - except in a very - what I thought was a most degrading way. Most of my - my father - and most of our friends in the neighbourhood were very keen gardeners. And - there were more horses in those days than there were motor cars of course, in fact the -
 motor cars were almost non-existent. And - most of the - gardeners - would give you a penny or tuppence if you would bring them in a load of manure. And - each morning - before I left school, I used to go round and - collect manure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh I got into ver
y serious trouble with my father, and - and mother. I used - used to go out each morning - to - get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 manure}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 , which I objected to very strongly by the way - and - I began to think of some ways and means of avoiding it. So I went out and I thought to myself, 
well - if I - take a load of manure home every day, or every alternate days, and the days when I don't take a lot of manure round, I cover the heap of manure - with earth I can put the manure that I do bring on the top and it would come up fairly quickly 
y
ou see, a little heap Which I did. But - it only lasted about four occasions. When I got a good hiding. The only other time that I earned money - was on Good Fridays. An uncle of mine had a bakers shop, and he used to make hot cross buns, and - I used to 
go round to - quite a large number of my mother's friends getting orders for a half a dozen hot cross buns, which I delivered on Good Friday morning. That was quite good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 But you left school then in 1904?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I left school about - thirteen, I think w
hen I was about thirteen - just over thirteen as a matter of fact. At that time they were making two entries a year into Sheerness Dockyard. Six monthly entries. And - they also made some con-cession that you could sit at an examination - when you were th
i
rteen and a half, instead of fourteen. For some weird sort of reason they wanted a colossal number of apprentices at that time. I don't know why because there was no imminent war anyhow. But anyhow, I left school, at least I - sat the examination when I w
as thirteen and a half, and I went - actually went to work when I was about thirteen and threequarters I should imagine, something of that I know I was the smallest boy of the entry. Which I wasn't very proud of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Can you tell us about the first day at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh my God. Actually the - I believe there would be about - I'm not quite sure about this, about half a dozen entrants in the fitting shop, the engineers shop. I remember my father taking me down - I remember him - saying well there it is son, y
ou go in there, in those big gates and you turn to the left and you'll find a ticket office. And you - stand there until the chargehand comes. I wasn't very happy. I think he saw that, he said, well cheer up, we all had to start anyhow. So in I went, and 
I
 - went in and turned left and - there were men rushing about all over the place, delivering their checks do you see, which they picked up at the gates, the entrance gates. And - ran across - and put them in a box, just inside the shop. When the bell ceas
e
d ringing, these boxes were shit like that and those who were late had to go home for a quarter of an hour. Very sad that was. But anyhow, I went in and - but the - the charge - the - charge - man - chargehand's runner we used to call him, who was a clerk
 
- he came along and he said, come on, and he took us - four - six of us I think there were up to the - foreman's office. Up - one of those iron staircases, going up like that. And - we stood outside in fear and trembling while he went inside to see the fo
r
eman, and then he came out again and - in turn he said you, come with me and the others stood there and - he took you to - some chargehand you see. Down the stairs - to the chargehand, where he handed us over. And the chargehand in turn handed us over to 
a
 fitter. Who was our instructor for the time being. And - the instructor - gave us a vice or - told us to stand at a vice, gave us the tools, and - a little piece of metal and told us to get on with it, filing or whatever the case may be you see. And - th
e
re we stood. Well I was a bit handicapped. I found I wasn't tall enough to reach the bench. Actually the benches - and the vices were - I suppose about normal size you see, and when I got up to the bench I was sort of filing up there you see. And they wer
e
 big vices, and - the bloke with whom I was working, oh he said, I'll soon settle that. And he got me a box you know, six inches high, and - he stood me on the box, quite a little thing bout - a foot square, and I stood on this - this box sort of - filing
, until somebody, bright idea - with a bright eye }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 kicked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
 it from under my feet. I went down of course. Caught the box, collected it, stood on it again and out I went again. Well this went on I suppose for about half a day really. And I was feeling very sad 
and sorry. Any how the following morning - I took - a bag, a little bag of sand, in this - and got there fairly early, and I filled this box with this sand. And - I waited. Stood on the box and I went on and - filing, felt that somebody wanted to come to 
t
he stores and - they came up and kicked - oh - of course the man thing was - was heavy. Anyhow, there was a bit of a shemozzle, this - bright lad wanted to fight me and all that sort of thing but - I was safe, in the protection of the instructor, so that 
was all right. But nobody ever kicked the box again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did they play any other tricks on you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh my God yes. All sorts of tries there were in workshops. I think the funniest thing really what did - did have a piece - a certain amount of humour I t
hink was when you were sent to the stores to get a rubber - to get a rubber spanner. And the number of us apprentices - who went very seriously up in the stores - to get a rubber spanner, and was told equally seriously, oh, tell Mr so and so that we haven
't got one yet, come again later will you, and like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 dammed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
 fools we all went back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What other tricks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I don't think tricks exactly. We used to have our little football matches, which was rather dangerous from many points of view. Playing footbal
l among working machinery is not too good you know. How we survived I'm damned if I know. But anyhow it was common practice, when the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 hargehand wasn't there of course. There was a fair amount of bullying but not - excessively. Although we did have one who
 was - an awful creature. He was about the worst. But mostly the men I thought - beyond cuffing you round the ears, which didn't hurt you after all did it - and - kicking your backside or things like that if you did something that annoyed them - there was
n't much really that you could complain about, I don't think. Anyhow, my reactions were really that with the exception of one bloke, I liked everybody. I thought they were a damned fine lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How would you annoy them, what would annoy the men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Wel
l I suppose if you went along, we had iron benches, and they were right along one side of the shop and along the other side you see, and - within the - the - particular area of the man's vice, that was his property, actually. And he was very proud of that
 bit of property. And a good fitter would - by the side of his vice on the right hand side of his vice, he would have all his - files - all regularly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 laid}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  out, so that all he had to do was to pick the one he wanted and go on, put that down, always in the sa
me spot, and do another one. Well if, as an apprentice, you wanted to - borrow a file off somebody - I'm speaking personally now, in my particular case, I used to think to myself, I wonder whether he's got what I want? And I'd look along the bench, do you
 see, and if I found that somebody did have a vice - a vice - a file that I wanted - well in due course that file would be mine. At least I would be using it, until I got a kick. Which was all - perfectly justified I think - really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How did you deal with this bully?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh I had a scrap with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 In the workshop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes. That was merely - that was - within a few months of my finishing my apprenticeship. I changed then from the - the little boy - I was four feet six and a half when I started my work. You know, I have to - often when I see kids and I see them about 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 fourth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
 feet six or something like that I think to myself, my God. But anyhow - I developed I suppose in a normal way. I did all I could to - make myself physically strong - for my o
wn protection. I did all sorts of things. Gymnastics - and - I remember one famous - thing of mine which rather annoyed my mother immensely. You know, you - if you go up a staircase - and you jump - you can hang on to the top storey. See what I mean do yo
u
. Well I used to do that - and hang on and pull my weight - as soon as I got home every dinner time for - dinner, pull my weight - weight about two dozen times which - I thought was extending my length, I don't know what - but anyhow, that's what happened
 
you see. But anyhow by the time - I was - nineteen I finished my apprenticeship nineteen and a bit, I suppose I was about the same size I am now actually. And - I was footballing, cricketing - I did play tennis. And - among my own fellows, I used to box. 
We all did a bit you know, mucking about. One of our - my friend - fellow }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 apprentices\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  father had a greengrocers shop, and we used to go to his stores to box. Which was terribly funny. I'll tell you about that later. But anyhow on this particular occasion I
 can remember going about after - lunch, and - seeing this horrible bloke - that had bullied me success - successively - over a long period - getting hold of a kid's arm and twisting it round his back and this poor little devil was howling. And - I don't 
k
now what was wrong with me - I shouldn't have done it really but I went at him. I said, leave that boy alone. Of course that had the obvious effect, he got - he got a dmaned sight worse. And before I knew where I was I had set about him. And my God didn't
 
he cane me. I should think - this - this fight lasted a hell of a long time, about quarter of an hour, and - he hit me everywhere. And he could hit. But I wasn't going to be beaten, every time I got done I got up. And toward the end I could hardly damn we
l
l stand, but fortunately I noticed that neither could he. Because - there were no three minute rounds you know. This would have gone on forever. If - if one of us hadn't collapsed. Anyhow - I did notice this that - he didn't seem to be hitting me at all, 
a
nd I seemed to be hitting him. And - eventually he went down. And he didn't get up. For which I was very pleased. Anyhow my pals got a - got hold of me and took me into the lavatory and cleaned me up but by God I was a mess. Ooh. But - I believe it made a
 marked effect upon this - bully. They did tell me some years afterwards that - he was never the same again. But - it was slaughter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 All the men were watching while you had this fight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes, yes. The funny part about that you know, the bell ha
dn't gone, we were - we - we'd started our fight - before - we were supposed to start work. And - after we'd been at it for about five minutes we were supposed - supposed - supposed to start work, but I did hear some time afterward that the chargehand had
 been given the tip to keep away for a bit, which he very nicely did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 They were quite co-operative were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes. I think - I think that - most of our chargehands - I don't think I met a bad chargehand really. They were - they had their job t
o do - they had to see that - we learnt our job, they had to see that we did our job. Then they had to - keep a certain amount of discipline in the workshop, which is very essential, by gum it is.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What sort of things would they use discipline for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 For?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What sort of things do you mean? What kind of discipline was needed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh - supposing - which was fairly prevalent, more prevalent today than it was then - that a bloke would - leave off work, wander off and have a yarn with his pal.
 Well there you've got a couple of men who are not producing anything aren't you. And that, in the eyes of a chargehand, is a heinous crime you know. It's a terrible thing - because after all, his point of view, he's got a certain amount of work to get ou
t
 you see, in our particular case we were all more or less working on engines. Ok. Those engines should be done, roughly on an average within a certain period. And - if not then you're keeping the boat back, you're going to get into serious trouble. At lea
s
t your not, the chargehand is. And naturally he's going to keep his own end up and keep - within limits, keep you at your job. Oh I don't blame them at all, I think then were - very justified. And this - I can say this - that - as far as I was concerned, 
I
 didn't like - the chargehands who - were strict - I liked the chargehands who were weak - weak-kneed, but by God, they didn't do me any damned good. No, no. No. In my view - as an apprentice, and as - as a craftsman - you've got - to submit to workshop d
i
scipline. If you're there to do a job - and you're paid a good wage, incidentally you're not - but - if you're paid a good wage - it's up to you - to - do a job - a day's work. I know in latter part of my career, when I had - control of quite a large numb
e
r of men, they always knew - that if I put - if they pulled their weight - everything was all right. But by God they knew they had to pull it. And I think that's perfectly fair. I think if you pay a man - incidentally that was a part of my job, I reckoned
 
that - the highest paid - workman in the factory were the people that I wanted. I didn't want any scallywags, I didn't want people on the low rate. I didn't want low rated people. Because they're no damned good to anybody or themselves. But if a man is pa
i
d a good rate of wages, then he should produce the goods. I'm not in doubt about that. And - in my - department anyhow - they all knew that. And - incidentally we had a damned good time. Discipline was very very easy - to maintain, it's - they - most of m
y blokes - were interested in their job, and they knew that I was interested in them - I think - the part - am I driver -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Where was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 This - on the latter part of my career in Farnborough. Farnborough, yes.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Engineering again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mm. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 The aircraft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What were you doing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I was - what - they used to call a principle foreman. But - in the re-organisation of industry and all that sort of thing, they call us a technical assistant. Technical officer. It 
meant exactly the same. Yes, it probably didn't - wasn't worth so much as a foreman. But anyhow that was - just a change of the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 When did you become a foreman then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh blimey. I think that was the only part of the war. Early part of this second
 world war. Before the second world war - I was on aircraft inspection for many years. At Farnborough, I used to do a lot of outside - what we term outside work is going round to various firms inspecting work - that is ultimately - for Farnborough, inspec
t
ing at their place you see. No, I did a lot of that, and when the war broke out - I was - controlling a small section of inspection, and - the head inspector came to me one day, just after the outbreak of war, and he said, I'm going to - transfer you to E
xeter, for the duration of the war. I said, are you? He said, yes, he said, we're going to have a branch down there - it was a branch of the defence department, and they were experimenting in the defence of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - these - big balloons, barrage balloons and all that sort of thing was a part of it. The idea of having it at Farnborough - at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Exeter
{\*\xmlclose} was because they were - far enough away from the bombing zone, also - we took over {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Exeter{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} university. So we had - a lot of staff at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Exeter{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}University{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - and - a - a
 lot of staff which we took on down there at Honiton Clist, just outside which is the airport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 But you were in engineering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How long were you working as an engineer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh before I became an inspector? Oh well - I became an inspe
ctor - in the first world war. Let me see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So you worked in the dockyard?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I worked in the dockyard - until 1916. My ideas on those days was to get away. But I didn't. For this reason actually. The state of employment in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} wasn't good enou
gh. The point was you couldn't chuck up a job, at least I - I couldn't, put it that way, I couldn't put up - chuck up a job until I got another one. I wasn't one of these brave people who say - oh to hell, I'll find something. I wanted a certain amount of
 
security. Of course - coupled with that was a fact that - my wife and I were - weren't married but we were keeping company, and - anyhow, I didn't - I didn't want - I wanted security, put it that way. So I hung at Farnborough - hung out at Sheerness docky
a
rd, until - 19 - 1915 I think it was. I think it was 1915. When I - made application - to the superintendent of Farnborough for a job as an inspector, which of course really was a damned cheek. I had never worked on aircraft - but I had fairly decent qual
i
fications as an engineer. Anyhow - I got a reply, yes, come at once. And it was a vastly higher rate than I had been getting, at the dockyard so I tootled off down there. And - at the beginning I went on detail part inspection. I don't know whether you kn
o
w anything about engineering do you? Do you? Well anyhow, imagine that to be an aircraft - it's composed of a few hundred parts isn't it. Right, well all those parts have got to be made, and - for the assembly, the - efficient assembly of all those parts 
t
hey've got to be within certain limits, otherwise they won't assemble, and that won't do it's job. OK? Well - the - what we used to term the detail inspection - was in each particular section of the factory, where these parts were being made, you would in
s
pect the individual detail of parts. And then they would be out - go to another part where they would be assembled, where you'd see the assembly inspector who would do the - that part, and then the final part like that would be the aeroplane, they would b
e
 all assembled up and would all, we hope, assemble efficiently, Got it? I went - first of all went onto the detail inspection, and then - the - the chief down there, the head inspector - came to me one day and he said, he said, oh - I want to put you on n
i
ght shift. I said, why? Well, he said, I'm going to have a - night shift of two men, he said, and I want you as one. I said, blimey, I haven't been here long enough. He said, that's all right. I said, all right. I said, oh wait a minute - what hours am I 
w
orking on night shift? He said, you start at six at night, you end at eight o'clock in the morning. I said, my God. I said, what about weekends? He said, well - you leave off work on Saturday morning - until Sunday night. Well I made quick calculation and
 I found - that I was getting more time off then - than I was on day shift, because we were working seven days a week you see. So I said, OK, I'll do it. So another bloke in my - and myself - went on, well that job was I thought was a cynicure}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11226495\charrsid2252871 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  we were not 
set any particular type of work to do, but we were supposed to be efficient enough to inspect anything which became - finished - and was put up for inspection, any part of the factory during that night. Which was quite a tall order. But anyhow - we got th
rough. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Going back to the dockyard, how long were your hours there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Hours? Seven in the morning 'til twelve. One o'clock 'til five I think, no - one o' - I'm not quite sure about this you know. It's like going back into the dark ages isn't 
it. I know what it was when I started. Let's start from there Seven o'clock in the morning 'til twelve, midday. Home to lunch. Half past one 'til half past five. That was five days a week, and - seven o'clock 'til one o'clock on Saturdays. I think that co
m
es up to fifty hours does it? Something of that, yes. Now there is one peculiarity about the dockyard, it only lasted one year. In the summer you worked longer than you did in the winter for the same money. There was no electricity. We worked with candles
 
and - gas jets. So it was better from the - dockyard point of view - to work in the daylight than at night. And - during the winter months - we used to leave off work at quarter past four in the afternoon, which I thought was wonderful. And we used to sta
rt in the morning at half past seven. Now that - that lasted a certain period you see, but - as the - the days lengthened so you went back to your normal time of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was it time wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did they start introducing more machinery while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I wouldn't say they did. No. No, not at - not at - in the dockyard. What machinery we did have - was improvised, there was only one - semi-automatic machine as far as I remember when I left. And that was for making - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16481126\charrsid2252871 screws}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 , quit
e an elementary sort of job, and - it wasn't automatic, in the way that today's machines are automatic. It couldn't be worked without an operator - to do it. It had a shuck, which was a hollow chuck, and it had a long piece of metal going right out, which
 
was gradually shortened as you went along on the job, your - your tool rack, was composed as far as I remember of four setters. One was a dye, to - screw dye, another one was to put a champer on, another one for something else and something else and the o
ther one's a parting machine, so that the operator - slewed round this particular machine - this - chuck here, to cut a thread, and then that would release is self, spring back and he would screw it down again, to put the champer on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Were there no electrical riveters for - instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Compressed air riveters. I don't think we had riveters but we had chisels. You know - how these blokes out on the road - cut big holes in the road, and make a hell of a din? Well, when I was an apprentice, toward the l
atter part of the time - they introduced - compressed air - chipping machines. They were things about that size, about the same size - as - a Black and Decker drill. And - you put a little chisel in and you used to use it for chipping and that sort of thi
n
g. For instance, when - a ship came into the docks, with a piece knocked of it's - runner, it's - propeller, they would - raise another piece onto the propeller, and the runner of this piece would have to be chipped off with this damned automatic thing. S
p
eaking as an apprentice, it was hell. And - it was hated by everybody, by the men who didn't work it because of the noise, and by everybody who did work it because you went home at night like this. So the - the chargehand - hit on quite - I thought was a 
good idea, until it hit me, that if - anybody didn't behave themselves, right ho, we put you on the next chipping job. And - I got quite an amount of that funnily enough.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Well I suppose I was a bit of a damned nuisance - but I can 
remember this, and - that going home at night, you know, you felt terrible really. I'm not joking. But going home at night you know you'd sort of - go like - not - you were shaking. But anyhow that was the first type of - automatic thing that I remember. 
W
e didn't have any electrical stuff, no. No. Of course I think you know - I've often heard women, including my wife - say, why don't they do something about those people who make big holes in the road - and make - disturb everybody's peace? And I said to h
e
r time - time after time, I said, by God I'd like to put you on the end of that. I mean - what the hell. We're only putting up with the noise. Those people are standing on top of it. They're not only putting up with the noise but they're - they're destroy
ing their nerves aren't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was there not a lot of noise in the workshop anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes. There was a lot - there was a lot of noise. The first workshop I had in Sheerness dockyard - was a combined workshop. It - was a machine shop and - fitting sh
op. And - it was - you - you know these old churches and chapels that had two galleries running down on either side, and with an end there - well that was how the fitting shop of Sheerness dockyard was. You went into - don't know whether I can make a sket
ch, anyhow - it was straight like that, right along there - but upstairs was a gallery, right along there was a gallery and there was a gallery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So galleries on three sides?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Galleries on three sides. Underneath here were - benches - right along t
here, right along there and right along there underneath. The whole of the centre was more or less filled with machines. Big machines and small machines. Now up on the top - on the top of the gallery, we had - a - a traveling crane. A bloke used to sit - 
i
n a little carrier, I used to think it was a carrier, underneath this crane, which used to run along on two rails. He controlled that by - going along to this part, running it - the carri - the crane along to a certain point, lowering his job, and doing w
hatever's - was required. Got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you belong to a trade union in the workshop?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes, I did, mm. I - became an apprentice trade unionist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Can you tell us about how the union was, the meetings and all that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 The union meetings to m
e were very interesting. Very interesting indeed. In fact - incidentally, the - the union meetings in the early days as far as I remember were very conservative. And - most of the members I would say - were Conservatives. So that when I - and one or two o
t
hers - who - were Socialist joined - I'm not so sure that we were - gratefully received. I know that - to be fair to the other blokes - if it was possible to twist an argument round to the Socialist side - we did so, would you like the - we thought that -
 
quite fair. But I'm not sure that it was. Now there was another thing that - I don't think was very fair. It was an idea of mine but we flogged it like blazes, that - in addition to having a meeting, a branch meeting, or dis - dis - discussion of business
 
- when the business is finished, we should have it opened - for the discussion of other things. And we should be able to book a speaker, to speak for half an hour. From somewhere else you see, on all sorts of things, didn't matter a damn what it was, all 
s
orts of things you see. And - they agreed. And - for the first year - we had most interesting lectures, on all sorts of things, religious, Melthusianism, we had two blokes down from Melthusians League and various things of - interest you see. Collieries. 
A
nd that went down very well, they got - quite popular. But - we gradually - introduced - a certain amount of politics. And of course it was one sided politics. I'm not sure that was very popular. But - I'm quite sure of this, that although it wasn't very 
p
opular, I think the large proportion of men there thoroughly enjoyed it. I think - they enjoyed the cut and thrust. Because - because - I mean we were chewed up no end you know. There wasn't any doubt about it. I mean a lot of these men - they had more wi
sdom in their little fingers than I had in the whole of my body. And - and for a bloke like me to tell 'em what ought to be done in - in this country of theirs - was quite a wrong thing. But it was good fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How many people went to the meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Before I left Sheerness it was getting very popular, and I think really - it was due to the fact that they were more interesting, do you see. Instead of going there and hear that so and so is sick and so and so is unemployed and - what are we going to do 
a
bout it mates, and all that sort of thing, they were having - something to talk about, and they were having something to - to listen to you see. I was say - anything from twenty to thirty. Some nights - if we had somebody - coming - who was going to be in
t
eresting - I think the chief really attraction, was if they knew there was going to be a row. And they would roll up in - in dozens. As a whole I wouldn't say - that Sheerness dockyard was very strong - from the trade union point of view. From the enginee
r
ing trade union point of view - there were three main - trade unions. There was the Amalgamated Society of Engineers. There was the Steam Engine Makers. And there was the Tool Maker. They - obviously - in course of time did amalgamate, and - became the Am
a
lgamated Engineering Union. They of course - have - had more amalgamations and they have become the Amalgamated - Engineering - Workers Union. And they have over a million members today. But the engineer of today or the craftsmen of today - bears no resem
blance to the craftsman of when I was an apprentice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Were people discouraged from joining the union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I wouldn't like to say they were openly discouraged. I don't think so, no. But I do think that they were afraid. Yes, I think that, I - I think that's quite true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What were they afraid of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
They were afraid I think - that - if - at any particular time, you had a foreman there who was very anti - that - and any of them got into trouble, that they would be for it. And I think that they wer
e very very much afraid of the fact - that there might, under - some circumstances, be a tendency - to choose a trade unionist who they would possibly think would - could be a nuisance, for discharge when the opportunity arose. I think - sorry - I think a
 
lot of this you know - is - not so much the fact - that a trade unionist is a nuisance. But - I think - the ordinary management of an engineering works is afraid of their potential. What can they do? And I think they're scared stiff. I'm quite sure of it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did the union at Sheerness ever interfere in discharges?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No. None whatever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 It was benefits only, that's all they discussed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
We had not the slightest - idea of when we - when men - men were to be discharged, why they were to be di
scharged or anything about it. To - I do remember on one occasion, when it was suggested to the management - that if at a certain time they knew they were going to be discharged, could the men know - right at the beginning so as to give 'em as long a peri
o
d of - probation as possible. They thought we were mad. I'm not joking, they did. That was the attitude in engineering in those days you know. For an engineer today - where he could - no engineer today in my view - whose only been in engineering for the l
ast twenty years - can have no conception whatever - of the engineers of fifty and sixty years ago. Not a shadow of doubt. Not a shadow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Were you ever involved in any strikes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Me, yes, oh yes. I was in the general strike.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I meant up to about the end of the first war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did they ever get near to striking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. At - at - at Farnborough - the - we had our shemozzles. But there was nothing particularly serious about it, except on one occasion. I think - to a very great exte
nt, the people with - with whom I worked, and I suppose myself, we were very very anxious to win the war. There wasn't any doubt about that. And we were very very anxious to do our bit. I do remember one incident when - we in the inspection department tho
u
ght we had a terrific grievance, and - we were prepared to go the whole hog. And I can remember that we held a meeting, and - we all said what we thought about it, and we all uttered our threats, and - we were going along very well, until - an old friend 
o
f mine who was older than most of us there, and he was a Scotchman and - he had had a very very long - experience in the trade union world, and in the engineering world, and - when everybody had been tearing their hair, he got up in the quite a calm sort 
o
f way he - he said, well, something - about this description, he said, well, he said - have you ever compared your lot with the lot of those in the trenches? Well of course we hadn't. Have you ever done so and so? Have you ever put your place yourself in 
t
he place of the management? Don't you realize that the management have got certain work to do at a certain time and all this sort of stuff, and really he put - the meeting on its footing do you see. And he was getting toward the end of his time and he was
 
speaking - louder. And - a little bit quicker, and suddenly - the top row of his false teeth jumped out. Oh my God. I can remember him standing there - and he jumped, and he caught them. And he - he tried to put them back. Well of course, then - the meeti
ng was convulsed. And to be perfectly honest everybody forgot their grievances, and we all went home comparatively happy. I think we'd better have a cup of tea don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 These are men in the workshop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mm. I mean this - this fellow that I was tal
king about, this Scotchman - it's true he lost the top row of his false teeth, but - by God he was sound. He was a wonderful chap. He knew his job. Good hardworking fellow, clean living chap I suppose - many people today, many - ladies anyhow - I'm sorry 
a
bout your sex - many ladies today would have - if they heard Jock - in the workshop would say, what a vile man. Not a bit. No. Another point about you know - about what I found about these damned engineers - they could swear - use most atrocious language,
 
but it all had a meaning. And - they used to take - well - what shall I say - they stopped swearing when they took their overalls off, really. I mean as a lad I went in and - naturally I - I thought I ought to learn to swear. I mean it sounds so - silly d
o
esn't it really, but - it's just the atmosphere of the shop. I mean for instance, if - a chargehand came along in those days, and said, oh dear me, old boy, you shouldn't do it that way - it doesn't cost anything. Well what they would do would - they woul
d say - what the bloody hell are you doing? Now that has got a colossal meaning, do you see? And the bloke knows - my God I've slipped up here. It means a hell of a lot. And - incident.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What were these men operating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What we term automatic machi
ne operators. They have a setter, who's the - toolmaker, the setter will go from machine to machine, say perhaps - up to a dozen machines perhaps, depends upon the tape - type of machine, and he will do all the setting of that particular machine you see, 
and all the - operator will do is just to operate, start it, stop it and all that sort of thing you see. But, in many many cases, owing to these - stupid system of piecework, the setter is getting much less than the operator. It's common practice. And -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
What bout the introduction of women during the war, do you remember that happening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I remember the introduction of women - during the 1917 - the first world war. I remember seeing the first woman - girl - come out of our foreman's office. This is w
hen I was on inspection then. I was sitting, and - the door opened and out came this fellow, and - and he was followed by a - a very meek and mild looking girl, who looked as - well like a pullet who'd laid an egg and didn't know whether it was the right 
thing to do. And she walked through the shop, followed - followed this bloke right through the shop, but you know, within about a month or so she was ruling the roost.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I'm not joking. She had a - profound personality, she had a very
 loud voice, and she was the daughter of a Colonel. Now - now what else do you want than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What was her job then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
She was - on inspection. In those days they developed - what were automatic micrometers, that was a - a bit weird, so that you 
couldn't make a mistake any harm. And these girls each were - on her particular gang, they each had one of these automatic - matic - micrometers, and they just - got on with the job, hundreds of them. And - she ruled them, oh my God.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 If girls hadn't c
ome in during the war that would have been considered a man's job?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes, that would have been a man's job. Oh yes, that would have been -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did the men object at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, the - no, they - most of them were very very glad to get rid of the
 job. I mean after all you know - there's nothing more soul destroying than to do the same thing day after day, day after day, my God.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did men go back to doing that job after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, it didn't arise actually because - during the period of w
ar you had so many of something, the same thing you see, didn't you. You had so many aircraft - of the same type. Well normally we didn't have that. So that you didn't require these huge number of parts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 But girls have remained in engineering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 O
h yes. Girls - girls form a very - important part in engine - engineering today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Do you remember any disputes about what particular job people belong to one union should do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No. Not one. Not one at Farborough. I never - I never - I never rem
ember any argument about whether they should have women - and that was a - quite an innovation, but as far as I know, they didn't - didn't object, I didn't object. And really I suppose - there's no reason why they should have done. They had sufficient wor
k, the craftsmen themselves had sufficient work, and that's all - that they were concerned with anyhow, that's the principle of the job isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 They weren't scared they would lose their jobs to the women after the war?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No. Now that could ha
ve arisen during this - this world war, the second world war. In - in the job that I was in, I had - about two dozen girls who were called women fitters. And - to be perfectly honest, I thought they were pretty awful. Well you can't - you can't teach - an
y
body a complicated - sort of processes in about six weeks, the whole thing can't be done, it's just not that, and yet they expected these girls to come in and within about a fortnight they were doing - quite elementary sort of engineering jobs but the fac
t was they were doing it - they were doing engineering jobs. The main people - were - very very intent to win the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What about the branch of the British Socialist party in Sheerness?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Well, I - I don't remember them, I - I would say that they 
- they were - quite - well they lined themselves up behind the Government. After all - in every country you have these - militant parties - but - wiping out all these militant parties, is another country. And I think - that, when - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16481126\charrsid2252871 Britain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  as a whole - has
 been faced with any difficulty in the way of wars - most political parties - have lined up behind the Government, said, let's get - let's settle this job first. Now you get too domestic - back to domestic things afterward.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You don't remember any conscientious objectors for instance at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh blimey there were some, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How were they treated?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I think they were treated - more kindly than they ought to have been frankly. What I - what I feel about that is this really - that - they took advantage of the laws of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}
}Britain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - to - sell them up the path. After all - you know, nobody likes going to war, my - by God my boy didn't like to go in the war, but he went. And hundreds of thousands of others went. But you get these conscientious obje
ctors, people who knock on the street doors asking you whether you love Jesus - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 In the first world war you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
They take the first opportunity to do nothing about it, do they. But they want the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16481126\charrsid2252871 protection}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  of the country.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What about 
the first world war, you didn't have them coming round like that then
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, I was once presented with a white feather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 It was a military town was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16481126\charrsid2252871 commitment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  in fact, the kind of the awareness of the war was probably stronger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes. And - and following it, yes, people were in - supported it more. But there was more - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose}
 I think, objecting, in the second world war, there was some there. But - the - but Guildford didn't have a lot of ideas about any - went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose}. We had a bus, we lived in - we lived in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose}
 and I worked in Farnborough. And we had a bus to take the workers home - each night and back to work in the morning. And - we'd start of from Farnborough, and you' get up Ash, and the driver would p
ull up and they'd all go into a pub - and after a time they would come out in ones and twos, and they'd settle down again and - we'd start for home. And the main theme of conversation - was Lord so and so, Lord Onslow, Sir Henry somebody else, whom these 
blokes - father's had worked for and they could tell you all about them, all their pedigree, and how nice they were to their servants, and God it used to - oh. But that's how they were.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 It was quite a shock after being in Sheerness to meet that kind of person?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Well at least in Sheerness they - they were very good men. No, they - they were nearly all carpenters. What about that occasion when we were in - Lens shop, Kay, do you remember that? Any? Well Len Winter. Len - Austin. Well this was a cous
in of mine, and he had manager - he was a manager of a shop in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Guildford{\*\xmlclose}
, corn chandlers. In talking to him one day in the normal way, you know, as cousins do, and a car drove up outside, he said, oh excuse me, and he dashed out to take the order from a la
dy who was sitting in her car. And - that was their usual - well we were - buying a present, do you remember that Kit some of our friends, I don't know who it was for, and we were in the shop trying to get a very nice vase. And presently the bloke who was
 serving us - completely - forgot us, some lady came in and he went up to serve her. So of course we did the obvious, walked out. But it was - Guildford was rotten with it, you know. Absolutely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What about the officers, were there officers at Sheerness
 who were treated in that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I don't know, most of the - officers that I - I - came into contact with were engineers. And I - I can't help - keep on a - keeping on about this but they are as different breed, there's no doubt about it. And - the - t
he Naval Officer in the name of - I forget what his name was, but anyhow he had the - capacity of going round on the job in the morning, going -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Who I thought were pretty awful. One was Pimple Rich. So named - so named because of his - face. But - he always did as little as he possibly could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 He was a good teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I know he was. I know, that's the tragedy of the whole thing, but he didn't teach. Oh no he didn't, you went there as a colleague of his, I was under - one of his victims. Then there was a - then there was old - Sleepy Middleton, what about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Which school was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 The boys school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 At Sheeness there was one board school for everybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mm. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mrs. R. No, there was another school, more than one. This
 was the main boys school really, then there was the technical school attached to that, later on. But - prior to that it was - there was a Church of England boys which wasn't over good. There was what we call the Bluetown boys, there were three boys schoo
ls then. This was the best one really. The results were good from it. I mean some of the boys who passed out there did remarkably well. And if they hadn't had a grounding -</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mr. R. Oh yes, but I say that was because they had something to aim
 at. Well I - I think - I think the more - more of the credit - went to the boys than the teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you enjoy it at school yourself there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I enjoyed it all right but - I - I think they were awful, frankly I do.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What was awful about them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
This - Sleepy Middleton for instance, he used to come in in the morning suffering from the night before - and - he - the first thing he did was to arm himself with the side of a slate, you know those wooden things that go round a - like the sl
ate - slate frame, well he used to - it was bout a foot long, and he always had that in his hand all the time, and you'd - just as likely get a - a cut across the knuckles with this chunk of wood as anything else. Well as regards teaching - not a bit of i
t
. Not a bit. And there's old - then there was Walter Blackmore, he had the less qualifications of - anybody there, but by God he could teach. Wonderful bloke he was. But what about the headmaster? Cor. I know he did, Kit, but he didn't do his job did he. 
Well you - you served under him after - after me, after I left. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did the teachers sort of emphasise more things like manners or tidiness?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Good Lord, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, they're not - you - you didn't - I didn't learn - how to beh
ave, my wife taught me that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What did the teachers think was important then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
As far as - far as I can see - the teachers there - taught up to a certain standard, they knew the standard, and that was the dockyard standard, and they taught up to 
that. But, beyond that - and any imaginative thing was - didn't come into it. And with regard to making the lessons interesting I can't see it I absolutely fail to see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did they favour the cleverer children do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did they favour the cleverer children rather than the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I don't think so, I can't see that, no, I can't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
What about children from poorer backgrounds, did they treat them the same way as the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I don't think there was any discriminat
ion at all as far as I could see, and some of my friends, not many, but some of them used to come without - without shoes and stockings you know. But I can't see any discrimination. One fellow I can think of - his name Alf Springett, always came without b
oots and stockings. And - but he was a lovely scholar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What about the other boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh the other boys never took any notice. No. Oh no, Springett was a friend of mine until I left Sheerness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did your parents come up to the school and meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. Oh good Lord no. And the teachers that I've mentioned wouldn't want to see them anyhow. Well - everybody knew that before you went there as a - as a teacher that - you could always find - \{BLANK\} school in the Conservative Club every ni
ght. Everybody knew it. We boys knew it when we were kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Do you think their politics influenced the way they taught?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I think they gravitated to the bar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was it a mixed school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Just boys then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 All boys, yes. Well the 
example was bad anyhow, Kit, from the headmaster downwards. When you think of a headmaster who when you have - playtime comes for the kids, kids go out to play. The headmaster of the boys school meets the headmaster of the other school, attached - and the
y walk across a field near the school, up onto the promenade, looking at the water and they go for a walk about a mile each way, and they come back casually about ten to - quarter to twelve. Can you wonder about the discipline. I can't you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Discipline was all right in the other school wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I don't know, Kit, I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mrs R. But you - you object to order at any time don't you?</subject2>

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Ay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You object to anybody that's going to order you. Anywhere at any time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, I - I see - I see the obvious. Even - but I believe in discipline.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Self-discipline?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Discipline. But there was no discipline in that school. No, if there was it was only when you went there and you exerted it. But it wasn't before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Were you a rebel at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I can't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I think you said there were eleven of you in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh eleven of us, yes. I was the youngest of eleven. We - we had - nine boys and two girls. Actually I only remember nine. The two elder boys - F
rank - and George - were - who came about in the - about half way down, had died before I - came on. So I only actually knew nine. And - seven boys. One, two, three were in the Navy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 They went in for life you mean to the Navy, that was their careers i
n the Navy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mm. Actually, I - tried for the Navy you know. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was that before you became and engineer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No, when I finished my apprenticeship - if anybody had said to me - I should be going into the Navy I should have laughed like hell, bu
t - one brother who got on rather well in the Navy - he - he was very keen about it. And - many of his friends who were at that time Warrant Officers - were advising me to go into the Navy. And I - I remember saying to one on one occasion, why - why are y
o
u so keen that I should go into the Navy, I don't want to go in? Good Lord, he said - you you'd do well, he said, you play the piano, he says, you play football, you play cricket, he said, you're made. Which rather indicated to me - how easy it was to get
 on in the Navy. But anyhow, apart from all that - I made application - finished - after I'd finished my apprenticeship - I was going into a - as an engine room \{BLANK\}
 you see, and - I made application, and they told me to report, I think it was Chatham Ba
rracks, for a medical examination, and they turned me down. Yes, to me that was an awful blow actually because - having taken such a hell of a long time to decide, you know, I thought it was all cut and dried. Buy anyhow - the - doctor said - we can't pas
s
 you in. I said, why? He said, you've got varicose heel. I said, I know that. He said, you know it? I said, yes. I said, all I want to know off you really is that - if I have an operation will you pass me in? Well, yes, he said. Now actually looking back 
I
 don't believe him at the time. I'll tell you why. When he was halfway through the examination - he - made many many tests of my chest, and I could see that he had a certain amount of doubt about it you see. In the end he called in the - his assistant, an
d
 he said, send Doctor so and so to me. And this - other doctor came in and they had - combined - operations, and I thought myself then, there's something funny about this. But anyhow I went home - made arrangements with the doctor, went up to Poplar hospi
tal of all places - and had an operation, and - within a fortnight of having finished the operation - I returned to Sheerness, and I presented myself for examination again. Of course they turned me down flat. So that was that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Your brothers became Warrant Officers then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. One - there was a such a thing in the Navy, they used to call the writers. Who we'd call clerks and secretaries today. Well one of them - had - he was rather - I suppose he was fairly well educated. Actually I always said to h
im that - he was very clever. And - I'll tell you what he did. He told my people that he - wanted to be a teacher. And - that was rather against the grain because - frankly we couldn't afford it. But - they decided to make this supreme - effort and he bec
a
me a pupil teacher first. And - he was there - a pupil teacher for about three years, 'til he got to the age of about sixteen or seventeen. Then he decided he wouldn't - be a teacher and he would go into the Navy. Well actually what - he had been after wa
s
 another three years education of course. But anyhow, he went into the Navy and he did very well. He - got a commission in the end. And he - in a way - being the eldest of the three who went into the Navy, he was - a - of great use to them, insofar that h
e
 could use influence, and being - a writer - he was the - secretary of the - Admiral at - Chatham - sometime. He could - pull a few strings. Which with one brother was very necessary. Anyhow one - one of them went to the training ship - at Harwich. No, ju
st outside of Harwich.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Ganges do you mean, near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ipswich
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 That's it. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ganges{\*\xmlclose}
, that's the boat. Well he went there and he got his training. He did very well actually. And - after a time he went - he was on the HMS Terrible. She was a four - four ma
sted boat - four - funneled boat, and she I believe she and the Powerful were the only two four funneled boats in the Navy. Anyhow, it's a man of war, and - he then was sent - to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}South Africa{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, during the South African war. And - the HMS Terrible was in the Relief of Laysmith I think. Anyhow, having - as he - she used to say - having cleared that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16481126\charrsid2252871 little war}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  up, they he then went to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}China{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. With the Chinese Rebellion. And after that he came home. I believe he was away then about four or five years you know
. In those days you - they - didn't have a limit of two years, that was all nonsense. You were away until you'd finished your job. Anyhow he came home at that time and then I got to know him more - better really 'cos I was very young. When he came home fr
om - South - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}China{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 I suppose I would be about twelve. And I would be at - began to then sort of take an intelligent interest that - that I had a brother who was a sailor. He became the Warrant - Officer at a very early age, and - I forget what - what ship h
e was on, anyhow, we had a - a letter one day saying that he'd got consumption. And that was fairly rife in those days you know. Particularly one these - boats. The ventilation was - pretty awful. The living accommodation was very very bad. And - you had 
to be fairly strong to survive you know. But anyhow - he had just got his commis - his - Warrant Officership then. And - they said that he was going to be sent to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Chatham
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} hospital. Now what - what would I be, that would be - I believe it would be about 1909
 or something like that. And - would I - would I meet him at - the station and - take him there. So up I tootled, only too glad to have a holiday from work - and - I met him there at the station and took him to the hospital. I know I - I feel - felt very 
i
mpressed, he of course was - given officers quarters. He had his own - rooms. And I felt very bucked about this. It's wonderful what things - have an effect upon you. But anyhow - in due course he got invalided out. And - by the time he was invalided out 
-
 Lloyd George had introduced his Insurance Act. And they wanted a lot of clerks. And - they held Civil Service examinations all over the country, for these clerks. My brother sat and he got a job. And he became a fully fledged clerk, and they sent him to 
- {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Birmingham{\*\xmlclose} I think, yes, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Birmingham{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and - when the war broke out in 1914 - he wanted a change by then and he - volunteered. And they were very very pleased to have him. And they stationed him in charge of the - defence of - Ramsgate. And while he was the
re he won the MBE. For doing - apparently there was a - I suppose it wasn't - couldn't have been a bomb in those days, it must have been a shot - some very big shell, but it buried itself - among a group of - houses there, and my brother went along and - 
m
ade it safe, and he got the MBE anyhow. Now another brother - was for a short time - a boy labourer in Sheerness dockyard. And then he joined up the Navy - in the - what they term the armourer's crew, dealt with arms - gun - guns, rifles and all that sort
 
of thing you see, and - he believed in enjoying life. To him - being in the Navy was not something that you sort of set your mind upon, and decide that you were going to do well at it. It was a - it was a sort of a job where you could have a damned good t
i
me. And he followed that through his life. And that was where my older brother - who was the writer, had a fair amount of influence is very useful. He got him out of many many scrapes. In fact he got him promotion to a first class Petty Officer once. Only
 for him to lose it again. But anyhow - he had a good time. And incidentally he - he died - about 1918/19 I should say. And he died in most peculiar way. And by that time he had - left the Navy, and he was - trying to get a job - in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, as a taxi driver
. It was in the early days of taxis by the way. When they were more or less changing over from the old handsome cab and the carriage and pairs and that sort of thing. And - he was in a garage one day and he - the bloke who was driving the - the steel car,
 
trying to get it out of the - gates - put it in reverse instead of - in his first gear, and it - went hell for leather at my brother who was standing at the back, and - squashed him there, anyhow he died. I've got a photograph upstairs I'll see if I can f
ind it before you go - all the - our boys in the fam - the family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What about the other three then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
The other two? Oh the other three. The eldest brother - he was an apprentice at a grocers shop. And - in due course - he bought a shop. This shop was in a very very bad - part of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}
}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Hommerton, I don't know whether you know it. Do you? Well his shop was immediately outside of Hommerton station. I can see the damned place now. It was an awful sort of place. It was a three storeyed house, and the
 shop - fair sized shop, about this size perhaps, but stores in the back, where he had his grinding machines for the coffee and storing all the stuff that wasn't in - ordinary use you see. Is this light? And - when I was - what would I be - eleven, twelve
, thirteen, before I - went into the dockyard anyhow, I used to spend my holidays with him. And - he had this big house, well quite a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16481126\charrsid2252871 comparatively}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  - big house, the shop, tons of biscuits, ham, you know, everything that a kid would like to muck about with, 
and I used to go there for my holidays. And - there I used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 Devour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  his chocolates and his - biscuits and and I remember one particular thing that I was very very partial to - he had one of those grinding machines for grinding up coffee beans in the store
s at the back. And - it was my delight for him to say, Stan - do me a few pound of beans will you? And I would go in there, and I believe I'd eat as many as I ground, I used to love them. But anyhow -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did he expect you to help quite a lot? Did you hav
e to help quite a lot when you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes, yes. Oh yes, I think I gave him an added freedom actually, because - stand - standing or sitting in a shop all day when you haven't much to do is a bit of a bore isn't it. Well he didn't stand there.
 I did. And - when a customer came in I used to shout out, shop. He used to stride in you see. But I got very very vivid recollections of how beautifully he used to cut ham. You know these - cutting machines today, well they - they weren't a cut - a patch
 
on my brother honestly they weren't. He - to see him cut a hock of ham you know, slice it across was wonderful. And you could go into his shop then in those days and you could have a - half an ounce of ham. You know, just about one thin slice and - enough
 
for a sandwich. He sold eggs at out - outside - on - Saturdays he used to employ three other boys. I used to tell him that he sweated me because he used to have four. But anyhow, these boys were outside - right along the outside of the shop - biscuits, bo
x
es of biscuits all the way along. Tuppence ha'penny, threepence and fourpence a pound they were in those days, and these kids used to shout out, two and a half, three and four a pound. On the other side of the door - on the door - were these big crates of
 
eggs. Varying in sizes from the small to the fair size. The small were about two or three a penny. And - the big - were I suppose a penny each, something like that. And - I joined the ranks outside and I used to have a very good time, no doubt about that.
 
We had a - fair of scales up there, we used to weigh up the biscuits and - that sort of thing. Sell the eggs. And - at that time, I don't know whether it's true, but - it was a belief - that if a man had had too much to drink - and he came along and he - 
b
ought about half a dozen eggs and ate them, you know, just broke the shells and ate them like that, that he would be sober. Now whether - whether there was anything in that or not I don't know. But nearby there was a pub. And people used to get tight ther
e
 - most awful sights I saw there, but anyhow a lot of these blokes they used to come along and buy half a dozen eggs and eat them. And - whether they staggered off or whether they walked off I haven't got any recollections about but - recollections about.
 But anyhow that was the idea. Now another brother -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
So he stayed for his whole life did he, he ran this shop for the whole of his life did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. Oh no. No, he - he collapsed - which ra - rather made me think - he collapsed in health. Which ra
ther made me think - that this medical doctor - was not such a damned fool as - I thought he was at the time. He - didn't get consumption but he got a complaint of the chest. And he had to give up his shop. He went into - insurance, and I'm quite sure tha
t
 he was very very glad - that he'd had to give up his shop 'cos he had a wonderful time after that. These insurance agents you know get money for jam I think. You only work in accordance with the work that you get - on your book, and if you get sufficient
 
work on your book - to keep you, fairly comfortably, there's no incentive to do anything about it is there. I know that he used to have two or three days a week off. I don't blame him. But anyhow, he eventually was superannuated from the - insurance, had 
a
 very nice pension too. Now another one - he was also apprenticed to - a grocer. A grocers shop in - Sheerness. I forget the name of the shop, but anyhow it was quite - oh Shrubsalls. It was quite a large shop. And they employed, I suppose half a dozen to
 a dozen - employees. And he served his apprenticeship there, then he left - and he went traveling, in the grocery line. And - then he became manager of - a Teechans branch, Teechans, Twtgens, they made tea. Anyhow they had many branches in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and he became manager of one of the branches. Then he became a commercial traveler. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So he finished up as a commercial traveler?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
He - a commercial traveler, then he went to Wolsey's the underwear people. And he took charge of their - advertising department. And he did very well, no doubt about that. They supplied him with a house which is a very large house in - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Leicester{\*\xmlclose}. I don't know what he earned, but I know he used to very very free with his money. But - he - contracted cancer. And he died abo
ut - twenty-five or twenty-six I should imagine. Let me see, that's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 There's one more I think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes, one more. Now he was the only of our - one in the family who became an en - an apprentice in the dockyard. You know the method of getting int
o the dockyard do you, by an examination you see. And - the numbers - of entrants into the - dockyard depended upon - the state of whether we were gong to have a war or not. That sounds rather fantastic but it is really true. If it was calculated that in 
a few years time - t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 hey would - we would be in - en}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
gaged in war, then obviously they had to have a good supply of labour. And they had to have labour which by that time would be trained. Well I can - remember very very plainly - that at that time when he - 
was an - entered the dockyard, there was something in the region of about eighty or ninety apprentices entry. There would be about - two or three dozen entrant fitters. A few shipwrights. Ship fitters, moulders, carpenters, joiners - you know, the whole r
i
gmarole that's - sets up an establishment engineering, but anyhow he got in, and - he was - rather disappointing my people because my people wanted him to be a fitter. For some weird sort of reason they had an engineering mania. But anyhow he became shipw
r
ight. Which was just as good anyhow. There's as certain amount of snobbery in all dockyards you know. Oh yes. You know, there were mothers going out saying my son's a fitter and yours is only a shipwright, that sort of tripe. But anyhow it was quite real.
 
But anyhow he was a fitter, he - was a shipwright. He got horribly fed up - with work, so did I, and - when the first world war broke out - he volunteered - to go into the RAMC. Now he - that would be about - let me get my dates right. I went into the doc
k
yard in 1904. So I finished my apprenticeship in 1910. He was six years before - no, five years before me. So he finished in 1905. Well - he got a transfer to Portsmouth dockyard - at that time because he was interested in building the first Dreadnought, 
a
nd he got an ent - transfer there and he was there about two years. And then he came home, we had a sort of breakdown, and - transferred back to Sheerness dockyard. When war broke out - he volunteered, to go into the RAMC, and he joined up in the - the Ar
my, went across to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and he broke down over there and he - they sent him home quickly. And he got invalided out. There seemed to be something - what shall I say - there was a sort of a physical breakdown among - many of my brothers you know. And I rat
her think - you could trace it back to my mother. Who - many many years after she was dead - incidentally she lived to a ripe old age. Mm. Many years after she was dead, I - sort of traced her family history. And there was a tuberculosis - background, the
r
e wasn't any doubt about that, which - as far as I can see, had run, or did run among most of us you know. Two - to a stronger or weaker degree do you see. Anyhow, he was invalided out - then - he got married, which - seems rather funny when you've - had 
consumption to get married, but - anyhow he did get married, and his wife - knew all about him. And he bought a shop - a greengrocers shop - and - he ran that greengrocers shop until the beginning of the - second world war.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did she help him run the shop then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh by God yes. She was a wonderful wife. And she still is. Oh Lord yes, if he was ill she would go to market four - four o'clock in the morning you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Had she worked before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Not in that line, no. No, not in that
 line. But - she had a Jewish tendency. She used to laugh when I said she was a Jew. But - she did have - and - she was very very business like and very hardworking, no doubt about that, my God she was. Because many many times he was ill, while he was at 
t
he job - in the shop you see, and - she would just put him to bed and carry on. It didn't matter. Anyhow, he became an air raid warden. During the - second world war. And - he did quite a - an amount of good work too, digging people out and all that sort 
o
f thing. And then he retired, so called, chiefly because - by that time his wife had got beyond looking after the shop, and she'd taken the job - selling tickets at - in railway stations. She became a ticket clerk. And she was all right at that too. And t
h
en they moved into a civilian house, and she was able to carry on her work do you see and he was able to carry on his work, until the war ceased, then they both automatically - ceased work. I say they ceased work, my brother then - was - somewhere near th
e
 age of sixty I should imagine. Anyhow - he got another job. He couldn't rest anyhow. And - he worked for a firm of solicitors, he started as a sot of messenger, and after a time he became their odd man, and - all sorts of odd jobs he did. For instance, i
f there was any repairs to their premises he would do it. See, having a background of a - shipwright, he had a wonderful set of tools and he was very very handy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you know what she did before she married him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, I don't know that. No, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did the other brothers marry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Every brother - that - except the one that - thought life was - one long - fun, were married, all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Do you know what jobs any of the wives had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 We'll start from the eldest one. The one that h
ad a shop, she worked in a clothing place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, in - that was a Jewish shop, making blouses, as far as I remember. At least I've only heard this you see. Now, the one - who married the bloke who we - he - ended up at - Wolsey's - I don't know what she
 did, her name was Myason. She had a Jewish - background too by the way. I hadn't thought of all this before. And she used to play the piano beautifully. Now I don't know what she did, but - I know what she could have been, she could have been a comedienn
e
. She could sit down at the old piano and she could sing - the funniest songs imaginable. And entertain, you know, anybody who came in. Now then, another one - was - who's the next in rotation? Oh Howard, his wife - worked in - a dressmaking shop in Sheer
n
ess. And - she had - two sisters. One of her sister's was my schoolteacher. Which was rather funny. Because - having a brother - who is very friendly with my teacher - I thought in - ought to give me a certain amount of freedom, until she gave me a good h
iding one day. That was the end of that illusion. Another one - let me see, how many's that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 The ones in the Navy that did marry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh, Sid, oh yes, his - teacher, his wife was a schoolteacher. She was a very big woman, and - she was a schoolteache
r - in - Aylsham - Faversham. And - she was quite a talented woman really. She - she was quite good to him I should imagine because - for a very long - large proportion of their lives together - he wasn't a fully fit man by any means, no doubt about that.
 But - she wasn't worried. Now the amazing part about them is this. That - they had - three children. Which you know is against all the laws of - of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 eugenics}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  isn't it. They had three children. One of them is a hulking great big bloke about six feet one. Str
ong as a horse. He is now just over sixty. He's an architect. He came down here a short time ago - another one - he had two daughters, and both of them were strong as anything, until one contracted cancer and died a short time ago, but the other one is st
rong as a horse. Doesn't seem to be any logic in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What about your two sisters, what happened to your two sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Two sisters, well - one - one sister, the elder sister - was - a woman who was always ill. And never died. You heard this story a
bout the creaking - creaking doors haven't you, well, my sister was a very typical example of that. I can remember as a kid that - she had to have - special treatment. May mustn't do that and May mustn't do that because she's not well. And I can remember 
w
hen I was quite a kid I was much younger than her - I used to think to myself, she never is. You know, in a sort of a boys way. But anyhow, she got married and she married a bloke who lived in Hackney. And he had a very big lot - a very large greengrocers
 
shop. A greengrocers shop to which he added a coal merchants - and when the shop - became vacant next door to him - he - it was a fish shop and he took that on as well. He did very well. And - what he made my sister spent. She was - she was extremely - ge
n
erous in every way, no doubt about that. Give anything away. But she had no value of money, no sense of - money at all. For instance I can remember - when I was quite a kid I used to go there as well for holidays - and - even - when I was a boy - it used 
t
o strike me - how - irregular it was for a woman who wants to buy something - goes to the till and takes out a pound and says, go and get so and so, and I thought to myself, how the blazes can they keep records, they can't. But anyhow, her husband died - 
during the second world war.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did she work herself then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. My eldest brother, who is in insurance remember - she was making an awful mess of the business - she had not the slightest idea of running a business at all, not the slightest. In fact 
- all the time if she didn't get up in the morning she wouldn't open it 'til midday or something like that. But anyhow - he said he would buy it off her. And he did, he bought it off her, he and another brother who went to Wolseys. They bought it - off he
r
, and - I don't know what the price they paid her. But she lived for some considerable time doing nothing anyhow. Then she bought a little - business - which was a little tiny shop - that sold chocolates, and all sorts of sweets. And - she only had that a
bout two years, that was in Hackney too, and then - as far as I remember she didn't do any more work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So she didn't work before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. Not to say work, no. She lived in various parts of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, she had - two boys. And two girls. The
 oldest - her eldest son was a fine lad, no doubt about that. And he took the place of his father actually. You know, he kept her - she never liked me to say that but I say he kept you straight. But actually he did. He organised her life for her. Somebody
 had to do it anyhow. But anyhow, he got married in due course, and he died about - a few months ago. Died in Harold Ward - Harold Wood hospital.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 And your youngest sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 The other sister - she - she - worked - in - a stationers shop, Greig Alle
n and Company, in Sheerness. They also produced the local paper by the way. Anyhow she - she worked there, she went there as a little girl, and she worked there and she became quite efficient. And - then she moved down to - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}, was it {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}? Yes, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and took a job - managing the shop, a stationers shop - which belonged to a Mr Tanner, Mr and Mrs Tanner. And she worked there - I suppose for about ten or twelve years. This Mr Tanner - he had built the job up - built the shop up out of nothing mor
e or less, and - he was a Salvation Army man by the way, so is the - the - the mother, and - my sister joined the Salvation Army. But anyhow she worked there for many many years, and I had - an aunt who lived in Ramsgate. Now this - aunt - was the wife of
 
my mother's brother. We're getting into complications. And - he - had a mineral water business, this is the - my mother's brother, he had a mineral water business in Ramsgate, but he - used to bend his elbow. And - I suppose it was necessary in his line b
e
cause - he used to deliver - very - bulk supplies to publicans and all that sort of thing and - he used to - have a pint or two while he was on the job and - anyhow to cut a long story short - he lost his job. He lost his trade completely. Now, my - they 
h
ad - a family, and they had an eldest son, who had the family complaint, he had tuberculosis. And this youngest sister of mine go married to him. Much to my consternation, and everybody else's consternation. She didn't get married until - oh years after I
 
got married anyhow, and I was - thought she was going to be an old maid, in fact I was rather hoping so because I knew of her infatuation with this - cousin of hers. Anyhow she got married. And - to compound the felony she had a child. And that was what I
 
thought was about the last word actually. Anyhow - after the child was born my sister - developed - tuberculosis. And she was living in Ramsgate at that time, and - we all sort of helped in some way you know to bring the kid up, and she is now - the girl 
o
f about fifty I suppose. At the beginning of the world - first - second world war - they were evacuated to Aston Clinton, just outside of Aylsbury. And - this daughter won a scholarship at the local grammar school, and - attended the local grammar school,
 and entered into - local Government service as a clerk or typist or something, shorthand typist. And - eventually my sister died. Now this is the amazing part about this, the most of my people who - w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 ere supposed to be - have been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 in - inherited the diseas
e lived to a fairly old age. This sister died, aged just over eighty. Only about three years ago. She left her daughter, and - her daughter - has maintained the flat in Aylsbury.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Her husband died much earlier did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 He died soon after they were married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Had he ever worked then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Not - not to my mind - not to my knowledge. But they told me that he had - for a short time after they married, he did buy an insurance book. Now whether that's - right or not I don't know. But, he - he would say really that he did no work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
So when you were a by which were the ones who were at home then? How many were there actually in the home with you when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I don't remember my brother - my eldest brother living at home. I don't reme
mber my next brother living at home, but I do remember him coming home - on leave from the Navy. And - you know, for the short - short time. My next brother, I don't remember him living at home at all. Because he shifted away from Sheerness, he was a comm
e
rcial traveller, shifted away from Sheerness, but they all visited very very often. The home was a home, there wasn't any doubt about that, it was a sort of a headquarters. My - brother Herbert - the one that didn't care - whether it snowed or whether it 
r
ained - he lived at home for most of the time. Because he was the only single one. Now the other one who was a Warrant Office, I he was at home for a very very short time. So really speaking - for the main part of the time - our house was inhabited only b
y
 my - brother who was a shipwright who was the next one to me - and the others who used to pop in now and then. The - the armourers crew - who used to drink - he always had his headquarters at home, always, didn't matter what part of the world was in his 
h
eadquarters was there and his clothes were there and he had his bed there. He was a delightful fellow in my mind anyhow, I - always thought that he was the brainiest man in the family honestly. He had a wide knowledge, he was - remarkably well read. And h
e
 used to write a very good letter you know, his letters were - very interesting letters, all about things which mattered, you now, not - I got up yesterday morning, I did so and so, not - nothing like - of a personal nature but - you know, they'd be inter
esting letters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did they all write home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes, they all wrote home, not all to me. But although I must admit - that - they treated me very well. They - all the family said that - I was spoilt, I probably was, I don't know, but I know they treated 
me very very well indeed, no doubt about it. Looking back I - I - I've done some most extraordinary things really. And my brothers have taken it all in the days work. For instance I had - the - the one that became a writer, he had a - he had a house in - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Gillingham{\*\xmlclose}
 - when he was stationed at the Chatham Barracks. He was then - secretary, it wasn't - didn't call him a secretary, they called him a chief writer at the Admiral of the Norr. And - it was a nice house, and he was there about seven years. But anyho
w, I used to play football and all that sort of thing - and - we used to - have quite a number of away matches in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Chatham{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, well if I didn't want to go home I didn't go home. I just used to stroll in their - their place and say, well I'm - I'll stay the wee
kend. And I never ever remember any of them questioning it. Never. Oh all right, yes, all right, well you know where to sit. Same thing applied to my brother in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, the insurance agent. The one in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Leicester{\*\xmlclose}. No, they were all very very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So you had quite a lot of holidays as a boy, going away?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, not a lot, most of my holidays were - spent - in Hommerton or Hackney.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 And you always went by yourself, not as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh no, we never went - never went with the family. Oh my God,
 my mother never had a holiday. My father never had a holiday. My father never had a holiday from the time he joined the Navy - the Navy - I've got the Navy on the brain - time he joined the dockyard 'til he got his pension. And then I've always said the 
reaction was so great he died. You can't - you can't break a routine - of fifty years you know, like that can you. I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How old was he when he died then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
He died about - sixty-two. And he got his pension just after sixty. Oh no, they never had holidays. They used to go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, to Hackney - for a weekend. But that was quite - quite an event.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 All of you went then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes. 'Cos you got to remember this that my father - in those days they - they never had Saturday off you kn
ow. The first - Saturdays I can remember - was - I think he left off work at three o'clock in the afternoon, or something like that anyhow. Anyhow, then it was reduced to - twelve thirty or one. And when I got there I think we left off at half past twelve
. But we always worked Saturdays. Well you couldn't have much of a weekend you know if you leave off work at three in the afternoon can you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you have sort of Bank Holiday outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Four holidays a year. Christmas Day. Good Fr
iday. August Bank Holiday Monday I suppose it was Easter Monday as well, I'm not quite sure, but there were four days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What did you do as a family on those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh nothing. Nothing. My father - I - as far as I remember him you know, he - he alw
ays had to work. I don't mean - had to work for payment. But there was always something in the house, that had to be done, he had his own house you see. It was only a small house. But he did have the savvy enough to - live in his own house, which was rath
er unusual in those days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 He bought it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes. Oh yes. It was a - very very small house. It was in the middle of a row of about - I suppose twenty or thirty other houses. You opened the front door - you did have a passage, but - the pas
sage - made the drawing room very very small. Then you had what we called a middle room. Then you had a kitchen. Kitchen and scullery cookhouse place. You had no bathroom. Upstairs we had quite a nice room in the front, over the front drawing room, and - 
t
he stairs went up in the middle of the house - turn right, turn left to the - my mother's and father's bedroom. Turn right - to the bedroom - that was occupied by - various members of the family. And then out of that room into another little room, there w
as another bedroom. No bathroom.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How did you manage for baths then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}
}Bath{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}? I made a few notes for this some time ago for you and I - I've lost the damned things. But - I've got a very vivid recollection - Saturday nights was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 bath night}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 . There
 was no doubt about that, and - whatever else happened - everybody had a bath on that night. I can remember - we had - looking out of the kitchen window - into the garden, or into what we called the back yard, there was - there was a kitchen sink in front
 
of this - window. I remember that kitchen sink in particular. -It was only a very shallow one about four inches - deep. It was yellow with age and it was chipped all over the place, and - it didn't always run effectively, so my father seemed to be everlas
t
ingly clearing the damned sink, but hung on a wall, the party wall between the two houses, were three baths. There's a big bath, a middle sized bath and a small bath. And - we used to call them the three bears. There was father bear, mother bear and littl
e
 baby bear you see. And - the mother bear - the father bear I assume, I don't know this - I assume they were the baths for my father and mother, because we never saw them bath anyhow. The routine - was that the - the youngest had the bath first. And - we 
h
ad a big copper which - in which my mother - used for boiling up the - washing and that sort of thing. And - the bathwater was cooked in - boiled in that. It had a fire underneath it you see. And - that was ladled out into this bath, this small bath, whic
h was then put on the table - and I was bathed on the table. And - I can remember having a bath -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You were being bathed then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes, I can remember - I can remember being bathed. My father bathed me, my mother wiped me, and - I can always remember 
this. Which is very funny actually I think. When I got to bed that night, because I went to bed very very shortly after a bathing, my head always felt cold. And - I put that down to the fact that my hair was washed, and not properly wiped. I'm pretty sure
 
of that. I suppose there were so many of us they got fed up with wiping it. But anyhow then my next brother, the shipwright one, he would take his bath, and so on - those that were home at that particular time would do their bathing. And - in due course a
ll the - the water - was pured down this sink, that didn't flow very effectively, and - eventually we all - tootled off to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you have a fixed bedtime as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
As a boy, yes. Yes, I had to go to bed very early. Seven o'clock anyhow - alwa
ys. Unknown - unbeknown to my people - they didn't know the whole story - they used to put me to bed, but I always used to take a book with me. And during the whole of the summer I used to read until it got dark. Well I - I couldn't go to bed - I couldn't
 go to sleep anyhow, I wanted - I wanted to do a lot of reading, that's all there was about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was there a regular washday in the same way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Washing day, oh yes, washing day was Monday. You mean washing the clothes? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You wouldn't have anyone in to help at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh my God, no. No, my mother did it all herself. I can always remember my mother's hands, on washing day. And I've never seen it with anybody else. If you put your hands in very hot water - and they stay in this hot water for 
a certain time, you get sort of little marks - spare flesh, on the underside of your fingers. I'll have to show you that one day. I haven't tried it for many years, but I do know that is true. But on washing day my mother - for some hours after washing, I
 
used - I used to be fascinated with her marks on her fingers. Anyhow, she used to do all the washing. We had - two lines - two lines out in the back garden, we used to have a very very tall pole - this is Navy by the way and we used to have two lines - on
e
 with - the top line which we haul - used to haul down, put the clothes on, and haul it up and that used to fly nearly the - the height of the rooftop you see, and then the next one was hauled down a little way and that was hauled up and that was - so the
r
e were two lines of washing out nearly always. There wasn't much - ironing done as far as my recollection takes me but we had a mangle. And that was where I came into play. From a very early age I used to do the mangling. My mother used to - fold the clot
hes and of course feed the mangle, and I used to turn like - like this, it was fairly hard work I suppose really but I used to enjoy it. I believe was paid a farthing to - do some mangling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You got pocket money then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, not - if I did the mangli
ng I used to get a farthing, I can remember that. But I can actually remember the beginning of my pocket money. When - people in Sheerness lost their husbands, or their husbands died, a very large proportion of them opened a little shop - in the front roo
m
 - in their front room. There was no license about it or anything of that, they just opened a shop. And they used to sell sugar and - butter, tea, ham. And according to their - clientele and what they demanded so their - trade would increase you see. Well
 
anyhow - I remember - getting up one morning, and seeing the shop opposite - the house opposite our house - was turned into a shop. And - I remember telling my mother that - it's very likely that - Mrs Las - Mrs Lascombe, I remember her surname, Mrs Lasco
m
be has opened a shop. And my mother said, looking at me - with a certain amount of contempt said, yes, I know she has, she's lost her husband. Now you know for some time I couldn't - connect - the losing of a husband with the opening of a shop. Because if
 
you lost your husband I thought you'd lost him, he wasn't dead, you just simply lost him, you mislaid him or something of that description you see. Until eventually I worked it out. But anyhow - after that I noticed that one or two of my friends went alon
g
 there - into this - this shop and they bought a farthingsworth of sweets. And - I being rather nosy - I wanted to know where they got their money from. And they said that was their pocket money. Well if they had pocket money I didn't see why I shouldn't.
 
So I put it to my mother. And - oh - that wasn't - unheard - that was unheard of our family really until they reached the age of about eleven or something like that. Anyhow I pressed the subject - and mother said she'd - see father. And - I remember getti
n
g very home - home very early from school that night, I wasn't going to miss - miss this, and - mother explained the situation, that - I - thought I - ought to have some pocket money. And - I pointed the fact that so and so and so and so, my friends had g
o
t pocket money, and also that some of my brothers had pocket money, I'd gone so far enough - far enough into it to find that out. And - my father said, yes, but they had to earn it. Then I said the wrong thing, I said, why can't I earn it? And - it was de
c
ided then that I should clean every Saturday morning I should clean the knives, all the knives in the house. And for that I received - one farthing. Now you know cleaning knives in those days - wasn't like - cleaning the cutlery today. They weren't stainl
e
ss steel. You had a - a knife board which was a piece of leather, and on that you sprinkled - brick dust and you went up and down like this with all these blasted knives. And you know with a big family - there were quite a number of knives in our family y
o
u know. And they weren't too good. But anyhow that was the - the first time I earned any money. I got a farthing a week - and that was subject to the approval of the - cleanliness of these knives by my mother. But I feel quite sure that she - I think she 
was - rather keen that I should get this farthing, so that - she wasn't too particular in her inspection.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you have to do anything else to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No, nothing much, except that I did - my father was a very very keen gardener and he had a lovely garden. I did collect the horse dung. Mm. Which I thought was rather infra - infra dig but - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Were your sisters expected to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
My sis - eldest sister no, never, she was always unwell. She always had something w
rong with her, there wasn't any doubt about it. But the younger one, the one that married the - her cousin, yes, she always helped, she helped very much too. She had a - tremendous amount of commonsense about her. Which made her marriage rather more - rem
arkable, to my mind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What about your father, did he help inside the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes. Yes. Father was always helping inside the house, he was always - always odd jobs. Always putting a shelf up here or - putting a shelf in there and - doing - doing
 a bit of painting or scraping or cleaning the sink out or scrubbing the garden - path or - always had something to do. And he always mended our boots you know. Mm. I should say that - my father - could trace the age - of his family - merely by counting u
p the numbers of shoes that he had to mend. Because when they were all - at home - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 although}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  I never remember that, there must have been a hell of a lot of shoes you know mustn't there. And I never knew - any of my shoes to be taken out of the house to be me
nded. When my father was alive. In fact - when - he died I mended my own shoes for quite a time. I - how I used to hate it, I wasn't good at it either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 They were bought new?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes. Yes. Yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What about clothes, were they bought new or secondhand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. They always had new clothes but - being the youngest son - I used to inherit the clothes of my brothers. Oh yes, that was quite - that was quite normal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Your mother mended the clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Yes, she was not a very good needl
ewoman by the way. She used to make my knickers, I can remember that quite plainly. And although I know it's an awful thing to say you know, I was heartily ashamed of them actually. No, they were - they were very very bad. Terrible things. They were an im
itation of the normal - plus fours that were worn - about twenty years ago, do you remember those things? Well they - I always thought their biggest virtue was that they didn't have to fit. It didn't matter, you had tons of room in them. Well, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 my mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  - m
ade my knickers - in exactly the same - plan. There was room for expansion. They were terrible things actually, no doubt about it. But - there it was. There was no money I suppose really, there was no spare money anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Would your father help with the cooking at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
YES? Yes, he did, mm. My father was a very handy man, no doubt about that. Oh yes, he could do anything. And he was always doing things. Dammit all, he used to scrub the - the chapel out - in turn. That was a small chapel that - tha
t one we always we went to. And - it wasn't a very big chapel, not - not much larger than say a modern garage really, it was built of wood - corrugated iron on the outside, and - wooden flooring. We had no caretaker. That chapel was wholly maintained and 
looked after by - people like my father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What denomination was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Primitive Methodist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Your mother and father both went on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes. Yes. My father - only went every other week. Now that was rather funny, because I can never ma
ke out why he didn't go every Sunday. And some - years after that - he gave me a clue. Quite unnecessarily, and I don't think he meant to have said so. But - he said, when I would - when I was in an - in a - an apprentice, he and I often used to have a wa
l
k - on Sunday evenings. And this used to happen about every other week, when he didn't go to - to chapel. And - I remember once - on one occasion, saying to him, why don't you go to chapel every Sunday dad? And he said quite spontaneously, I can't afford 
i
t. Now that didn't sink into my - you know, I didn't think about it until some time afterwards. And then I realized why it was. My father never gave less than sixpence in the collection. He would never give anything under sixpence. And that was quite a lo
t of money to him. So rather than give less than sixpence he would stay away once a week. Once a fortnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You didn't feel as a boy that they had a struggle to make ends meet though?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No. I - I do remember this, that - as a boy I didn't like 
going to the butchers shop. And I'll tell you why I didn't like going to the butchers shop because - I knew - that what we bought there was very inferior. I mean while people were getting - their steaks and all that sort of thing, and I was lining up for 
twopennyworth of pieces, it didn't sound to me to be very good. And I used to hate it like hell. On the other hand - I suppose - that represented really the - financial position of my family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How many times would you have eaten meat a week then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I can't remember we ever went without it to tell you the truth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I seem to think so, yes, I don't think that we went without meat at all. No, I don't think so. It was an inferior sort of meat - I'm quite prepared to admit that, in fact
 I'm damned sure it was. And I'm quite prepared to admit that - what was left over today was eaten tomorrow. It was hashed up and my mother was rather good at hashing up stuff. Which - I didn't think much of. But there it was. But we never went short. No,
 never.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Could you tell me what a typical day's meals would be like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I know we used - used to have a lot of rice pudding. No, I would say that the ordinary meal - would be - a stew. Probably on a Sunday we would have a joint. Yes, I would say on 
a Sunday we would have a joint. I won't say that the helpings from this joint were very - lavish. I'm prepared to think they were fairly frugal. But - it was there, we had it, we had veg - vegetables, my father used to grow vegetables by the way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Which vegetables would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Potatoes, cabbages and brussel sprouts and all that sort of thing, the normal. And he had an al}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 lotment at the back - the garden}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  at the back of the house. So that - that was well provided for. On the Monday I suppose we would have cold meat perhaps. And - we would have some pica - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 piccalilli}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 , or some pickled cabbage or some pickled onions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did your mother make the pickles then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, she didn't make the pickles - my father always used to pickle shallots.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 He did it himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes, he did all them. As a matter of fact after we were married, I used to pickle shallots, I grew shallots - for many years, and I used to pickled shallots. Until my wife said she couldn't stand the smell of them, so - but frankly I
 used to rather like them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So the main meal was at midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What did you have in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
We had - oh in the morning, toast. That was a treat by the way. If I was good I was allowed to toast my bread. If not I had ordinary - bread and margarine or bread and butter or something of that description. And nothing lavish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You just had toast then, not an egg or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Pardon? Very very unusual. If I was ill - I had an egg. I rather used to enjoy being ill and - under those conditions. I had an egg but - not as a tiny kid, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you have tea or supper later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, I had nothing after tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What would tea consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Had tea. Bread and jam usually. In fact I think it was always bread
 and jam. We never had what the north country people called a high tea, I don't remember that at all. It's always bread and jam. And cake, my mother used to make cakes of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 She didn't bake her bread though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What did she cook on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh we had a kitchen range. You've never seen them of course now do you. It was a - about that size I suppose. The fire occupied about that amount, and - the - stove - used to be about that size, not on the inside, the inside would be about 
that size you see. And - the - fire was there, that would be about that height, underneath was ashes, and that would be - up to the same level as the stove do you see, the open stove. And there was always quite a big fire, as far as I remember. I don't re
m
ember - funnily enough I don't remember any shortage of fuel. There always seemed to be plenty of coal. Mind you it was - enormously cheap you know. And we always had a good fire, and - my mother did all her cooking on that. It didn't - it didn't have a l
ittle tap, now in - in later life I used to see - those {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}kitcheners{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - what had a boiler on the other side, and a tap, that you could let the water out of - hot water out, but I - we never had that. The - the - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}kitchener{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - was a very effective - cooker. You k
now the modern gas - stove - has the gas burning in the - in the stove itself doesn't it? The kitchener, the old fashioned kitchener - had heat supplied - on the side, and over the top. But no - nothing - of a heat giving nature was inside the stove. Now 
t
hat was much purer than today's gas. In later life - I got very annoyed about these damned gas stoves because it did seem to me - that - you - you had your gas jet going full belt in the bottom of your gas stoves - halfway up at the back - you had - a lit
tle aperture of which the foul - air went out of. But the whole of the gasses }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  un}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 brunt gasses went into your meat and that sort of thing. And I took a rooted objection to that, so much so - that my wife and I - saw an advertisement in one paper - of a sto
ve which had - instead - it was a portable thing, it's - oven was bout that size, and on this side - was - an aperture, over that, passing over the top of the oven, and here you had - a row - a jet row - a row of gas jets which supplied the heat, to the i
n
side of the oven, and over the top. But no gas went inside the oven. We had that for many years. Well we bought that, I think it cost about forty-five bob or something like that. And we never saw another one all the time we had it. I - I made up a little 
table so that it was instead of being - low down, it was body height you see so my wife could - and we had that for many many years, for - until before we came here anyway. And it cooked beautifully. Well those old {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}kitcheners{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} did, they cooked a - wonderfully well. Very well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you have any tinned food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Any what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Any tinned food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. Pineapple. Pineapple we had. I don't remember any other tinned food at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Corned beef?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I believe corned beef was after my time, I'm not sure
. I wouldn't - I wouldn't like to commit myself on - on that. Although I have a recollection - that my brother in his grocers shop - had fair sized tins of corned beef.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You don't remember eating it in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. I think he did - I think he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you eat fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Not a lot. Most of the fruit that - we had - I'm sorry to say I pinched. Well the - we didn't have a lot of money to spare for fruit I suppose so my mother never bought it. At least, not that I remember. Rhubarb she grew in
 the garden by the way. But - fruit - apples, pears - we never had an apple tree in the garden. Just before I left Sheerness, no, after my father died we moved into a house that had a pear tree. And that to me was wonderful. Never seen a pear tree in a - 
in a garden before. But we had one there. No, the - the normal apples that I had - were pinched out of orchards. And there were a fair number of orchards in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} as you probably know. And - even on the Isle of Sheppey there were orchards. And - I used to pi
nch them, that's all there was about it. I am quite sure of this, that - the owners were quite aware of it and they sort I'm quite sure of that. But they - didn't seem to worry a lot. Sometimes you'd hear a stentorian word like, get out of there, and you'
d all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 skim foot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 . But - nothing - nothing untoward happened to you.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You didn't catch rabbits I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No. No. No, I never - never did any - poaching like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did people in the town get rabbits do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I don't remember tha
t they did, we used to have rabbit sometimes, but I don't remember that they were poached in any way or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Just bought off somebody coming round maybe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
People used to shoot them with a shotgun you know. I know that because they used to take the shots out of 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you have fish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Fish, yes. Oh yes. Now the fish - I don't know whether you can imagine - do you - ever - can you ever picture - these hand shucks that had two wheels, two - two wheels down there, a shaft here - and - a slopin
g - board, running from there to there. Well that's how they used to bring round fish. There was one celebrated bloke in Sheerness - we called him Blower Johnson. He used to sell fish - he used to buy it, I should imagine, off the fisherman who came ashor
e
 on Sheerness beach, and he used to buy the fish, and - push it round on his truck and sell it to the people. Shouting like hell all the time, and as he - continued - going round the - town so he - used to get tight. And - I think the fact of the matter w
a
s, he - as he went around you see he got more money I suppose and - I suppose he couldn't keep money, that's all there was bout it. And - he couldn't pass a pub. And - he used to - get tight very very frequently almost daily, and to see Blower Johnson fig
h
ting with his - his truck when he was tight - was really something. But there were quite - a number of fish shop in Sheerness too, quite a number. Shell fish as well, oysters. An uncle of mine had oyster beds - in Sheerness, or Queenborough, you know, jus
t outside of - Sheerness, and also at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West Mersea{\*\xmlclose}. That was a - my - my mother's favourite fruit, was - oysters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So you ate quite a lot of oysters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes. Oh he used to bring them home in bucketsful. My - my uncle did. He was a Salvationist by the 
way. And - very fervent when in prayer. But - a good fisher - a good fisherman, and - a good businessman I suppose. They said he was fairly rich by the time he died, I don't know but - I know that he did have quite a nice house in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West Mersea{\*\xmlclose}. He had a hou
se in Hooe, up the Medway. That was more like a cottage where he had oyster beds. And - he had a house, now where the hell's were - oh he had a small place in Queenborough. In other words - near - his three lots of oyster beds he had some sort of habitati
on, and he could put up for the night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did your mother make jam?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. Not as far as I recollect. Very very - no, I can't recollect it. No, we were - we were more likely to make jam. Oh yes, when we - after we were married my wife and I used to ma
ke jam. Mm. Yes, we used to go blackberrying - can't say I liked it, we used to go blackberrying, and - get home and have tea and then make this jam. Jelly mostly. Because - neither of us liked the pips, and we used to make jelly mostly. Very nice too.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did she make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
My mother? Brimstone and treacle. Now there's a - something else I'm trying to think of. It'll come to me later, I - I forget the name of the damned stuff. Anyhow, she used to make that. It was horrible stuff. Don't thin
k I'm vulgar but it looked to me like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 diarrhoea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
, it was awful stuff. It was - sufficiently objectionable to - to make anybody well by - just by looking at it. But this - brimstone and treacle - was terrible stuff too you know. Anyhow my wife will probably 
think of some of these medicines, she's jolly good at medicine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 She made medicines then did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No, she used - she's very good - she had studied a lot of medicine you know, my wife, sort of a hobby of hers. And - she - if you want to know what'
s wrong with you - you've only got to ask her. But she is - quite honestly she's very good. She's never seen a doctor since she were - had her baby you know. No. She won't see a doctor, that's all there is about it, she said, I know more than he does. Whi
ch probably is quite true. Continuous effect upon the audience or the reader than if you don't hear it. Also I had ambitions of - either - going in for politics or - trade unionism you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 When was that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh my God. It was before I finished 
my apprenticeship, it must have been about 1909. And during those days - of course - to be a Socialist was an unheard of thing really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you go to evening classes then, to learn the shorthand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, I - I went to evening class
es - I also learnt typing that way, which - I'm not a good typist but - it does - it saves me a lot of writing, and I can't write, my - writing's pretty awful really. I - I always think ahead of what the hell I'm writing you know, which is a very big disa
dvantage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 There were one or two things that I got a bit sort of muddled about.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Yes, by all means.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Your father, after he was in the dockyard he never did any sort of casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No. Not as far as I know. No. The part 
time jobs of course rose in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was that the first job he ever had or did he have anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, as far as I know that was the first job, but I'm a bit }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 hazy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
 about that, I wouldn't - I wouldn't like to commit myself about that. But - m
y impression - from - aunts and uncles and that sort of thing, is that that was his only job. There was one thing I did - I was thinking about - on the - the last night that you were here. I think about these things in bed you know. You asked me whether -
 my mother had had any job other than the home. And I said no. Well that - that I suppose is perfectly true except - she did have a little general shop. In - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Sheerness High Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I don't know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 exact}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  - except it - expect it's existing today. But it was a li
ttle shop, and I was born in that shop. Incidentally - during the latter part - of - my apprenticeship - when I was sort of - taking wings and feeling my feet and that sort of thing you see, I was complaining about - conditions, politics and trade unionis
m
 and work and God knows what, and one - one of my brothers said, well anyhow, he said, we hoped that you wouldn't live. Quite - quite honestly he said this - said that, I said what do you mean? Well, he said, you must remember that - I think it was Herber
t. I'm not quite sure, well he would be about ten years older than me you see. And - he said, what you've got to remember is this. That when you came along we were utterly fed up and sick and tired of the napkins being washed, on the line, and }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6825366\charrsid2252871 squalling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  kid
s. He said, so - the brothers and myself all - brothers who were older than me and myself, he said, we were - almost praying that you wouldn't survive the ordeal. Which is understandable. I mean, a small house - napkins all over the place, drying, being w
a
shed and dried - no - adequate - convenience for getting - bathing the kids or - all it meant in those days really was a - was that the kids were a damned nuisance. They were a nuisance. What it did have - what it did do was - the elder brothers and siste
rs always knew that with the arrival of each kid - their sleeping accommodation was reduced. And reduced to a very great extent too. I mean three and four in a bedroom was nothing. It was quite normal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How long were you in this place where the shop was then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Well I don't remember it. I have no recollection whatever of the shop of any description. All I know - is that - my mother ran the shop, and I suppose she did fairly well, I don't know. But I do - I do know this - that - even up to the time th
at - when I was about seven or eight - she was still suffering from bad debts. She was out of the shop - but she was still collecting money weekly from bad debts.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 She collected it herself then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Well sometimes I had to do it. That's why I knew about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Why do you think she gave it up then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Well it got too much really. You can't - you can't effectively run a shop - which is a full time job - cook a dinner for - the kids and a husband who's working - attend to all the - housework, the m
ending of clothes and the hundreds and one things that are to do. Can't do it, at least I don't think so. Something's got to suffer. I mean - you pass your life - dashing about inside the house listening to the bell for somebody to come into the shop, and
 then dashing in the shop. That's not good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 There was never anybody else like a lodger or another relation living there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Later on they - lodgers came. And - but that was when most of the - the - my elder brothers and sisters had left home you see
. And - I can remember this, how deeply I resented these lodgers. It's almost true to say I hated the sight of them. And I know I was very very rude. Oh yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What kind of people were they then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Mostly Naval people. You see, Sheerness - being
 a dockyard town, and a Naval - town, you had a lot of coming and going of the Naval people. And - I believe - she said so anyhow, my mother had quite a reputation among Naval - people, coming for a three weeks - three months and that sort of thing do you
 see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Would they be seamen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No, they were - they were - mostly Petty Officers, or Warrant Officers. Mostly Warrant Officers as far as I remember - as far as I remember, they used to bring their wives with 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 She gave the all meals as well then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. They used to live aboard their boats or in the barracks. All their meals were supplied in there except - a tea, and breakfast, which my mother gave - but if they came with their wives, they used to have two rooms, a bedroom and - a liv
ing room you see. But as I say that was when the housing of - of the family was a little bit easier.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You had a parlour didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes. We had an extra room downstairs which I think is very bad planning actually. You know the normal type of hou
se - they're all joined together - about fifty or sixty of them, one long row, all the same design - they had a - a small passage, in some cases they didn't have a passage, they - you opened the door straight into the - front room. It's a small front room
,
 you came out of the front room and you went down a passage to the kitchen but on the left - halfway down the - this passage there was another room. Which was always fairly dark. Insofar that they had a very very small room - small - aperture as a window.
 There was hardly any - any light got in the damned room anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Which room would she let then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 That was the middle room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 She let the middle room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes, she let the middle room as their living room, and one of the bedrooms upstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you ever eat in the parlour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Very very rarely. Very very rarely. I suppose we did, I can't really - remember that. But - usually - our kitchen - our - meals were served in the kitchen. It saved work - which was a very big consideration. And it was much more convenient.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Would you all sit round the table together for meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You had your own places, the same places every time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 More or less, yes. Oh yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Would you have grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you have to wait 'til the end to go or could you go when you finished?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh no, I wasn't allowed to sit - I wasn't allowed to get - to leave the table. Another thing I wasn't allowed to leave was food. Oh no, what was given to me I had to eat. You clear 
your plate up Stanley. It didn't matter if you liked it or not. That was quite a secondary consideration.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 So you couldn't choose at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh my God no. No. Oh no, it wasn't - it wasn't a matter of my saying, mum, I don't like so and so. Oh don't
 you? Oh well, you get on with it. You're - you'll learn. Of course - the - I would say really - that - by the time I was - being able to think say, from about ten or twelve onwards - I would say my mother - was just getting out of the stage when she was 
r
eally hard up. You see, with a lot of children - she must have been hard up, must have been. But these - at the time that I'm speaking about now - most of 'em had left home. And so it made things comparatively easy. But my mother would still say - sufferi
ng from the effect - of the period when - you couldn't leave half a potato on your plate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Would you sometimes see her have less food so that the rest of you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I don't ever remember that. No, I don't ever remember that. Probably it 
didn't happen really. For the reason as I've just spoken.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you feel that they were having a struggle to make ends meet yourself?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. Not the slightest. It's most amazing I think you know - how unsympathetic children are you know. They're real - they - it is really amazing when I think about it. I mean - the fuss that I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361306\charrsid2252871 kicked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
 up because they wanted me to go to the dockyard. Utterly selfish, completely unreasonable. But - I didn't care a damn, it didn't affect me at all. And - if anybody had sa
id to me, but - you must remember that - it's going to affect your mother's and father's happiness I shouldn't have believed them. It just wasn't - didn't occur to me. I mean that was my business as far as I was concerned. I still wish that they - they ha
dn't insisted upon it but - I can quite understand their idea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Your father was never ill or out of work while you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
My father never had a day's unemployment. Neither have I had act - actually. He was never ill, I never remember him bein
g sick. Never. But it obviously - to me now looking back, he must have been ill at certain times, but he just hid it and didn't worry about it, just continued going to work. Well he couldn't help it. If you were out of work - away from work you didn't get
 any money. You had no sick benefit in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Didn't they subscribe then to any clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Sick clubs, yes, but that was a - the - the sick benefit - and clubs like the Oddfellows and the - Reccabites and Forresters and - Druids and that sort of thing, they were in about five shillings a week. Couldn't leave much on that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 But your parents did subscribe one of those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Mostly, yes. Yes. And - in those days we had - what we called a - called a club doctor. I forget the name they called th
emselves but there was a certain committee in Sheerness - who - came to the conclusion that it was an awful thing to have to spend a lot of money and - paying doctor's bills. So they clubbed together, and - by the payment, I think it was tuppence or three
pence a week - they had their own doctor. I suppose that's a forerunner of the - National Health. I can remember his name, he was a nice fellow. Doctor Mortice was his name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You remember him coming then to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Yes, oh yes, yes. Oh he was g
reat friends with our family, he - I think he was rather fascinated to - you know, there's such a hell of a lot of us and we were always sort of arriving and - oh yes, I rather liked him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Going back to meals, were you allowed to talk at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 O
h yes. Yes, there's all a lot of - always a lot of talk. Wasn't always intelligent talk, but - there was always a lot of talk at meals. And a fair amount of then I suppose a fair amount of - horseplay really you know. Unknown to my mother, kicking under t
he table and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did they insist on your holding a knife and fork in a particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 And sitting up properly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh yes. When I see these kids nowadays - walking about, slouching, humpty backed, dirty looking, I 
think to myself, my God - I mean - whether their mothers and fathers are proud of them I'm damned if I know but - I know to me they look an awful lot. And some of their table manners are very despicable. They have a - I suppose they look upon a meal - fro
m a utility point of view. Your there to do a job of work, you want to eat down - eat it as quickly as you possibly can. And that's about what they look like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You didn't look at it that way then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, I didn't mind, I don't ever remember - objecti
ng to the fact that I had to sit up. I wasn't allowed to - sit as I see kids, with two elbows on the table eating like this. That's about the last word, I saw a kid the other day - I said to my wife, my God, look at that kid over there. He was about eight
e
en or nineteen, quite a nice boy. But it was obvious that he hadn't got the faintest conception of - how to hide a knife - how to hold a knife and fork or how to behave at all. Well they hadn't been taught. In fact I should say - roughly - that there was 
m
ore table manners taught by the parents - and more tuition in the homes in those days - in spite of the fact they had big families, then there is today with all the education the mothers and fathers start off with. They don't seem to worry about their kid
s anyhow. I may be wrong, but that's how it strikes me as on outsider.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you find your parents were easy to talk to when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
My father was very very easy to talk to, so was my mother. My mother - was rather a - in a way, I'm going 
to say - I would have said she would have been a very very good actress. She - she always took the leading roles in the - you know these dia - dialogues that - they used to have, and these - don't you? Well there was a large number of dialogues that were 
-
 written over a period of years - which - Sunday schools, little chapels and churches, used to act in when they gave a concert. They used to give a concert to raise funds and - always supply their own - artists and their own - dialogues you see. I remembe
r
 many many dialogues - Box and Cox. You probably remember that. I can't think of the names of them now but my - anyhow my mother was always one of the actress in the - the dialogues that were - acted in the Primitive Methodist church. And my brother that 
my wife spoke about as being a good comedian, he was always a damned comedian too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 You had to go to Sunday school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Oh Lord yes. Yes. I used to go - this is - very early days. I used to go - to Sunday school, which was at Bethel Chapel in 
the morning. That was at half past nine as far as I remember. And we used to leave there at half past ten. Then - I used to have to walk to my mother's chapel, which is the Primitive Methodist chapel, and - sit there until after twelve, listening to local
 - preachers and that sort of thing. The afternoon I again went to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bethel{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 chapel. And then in the evening probably - I would go to chapel in the Primitive Methodist chapel in the evening. If I could dodge it I would. But - that was the usual method really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Were there any sort of church clubs that you joined?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Toward the latter part of the time, this would be - about 1910 or 11 perhaps, maybe a year or two before, the Bethelist - the Bethel Chapel ran a club. What I suppose today would be called
 a youth club. And - we had a nice little building. It was a part of the - chapel properly, and we had a billiard table. We had a ping-pong table. Played chess and draughts and all that sort of thing. And that was open every evening in the week. The - big
gest night of course being Saturday night because we were all - all free. But that was a very very good run thing that really. We had a good football team too. My God we did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Was there a temperance club, was there a Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No, I never att
empted - went to any temperance places. I don't know why but - it's always struck me that - having - to sign the pledge was rather stupid. It always seemed to me that if you wanted a drink there was no reason why you shouldn't have one. If you wanted a dr
i
nk there's no reason why you shouldn't have a drink - providing you didn't interfere with the happiness of other people. That's all there is about it, to my mind anyhow. This - signing the pledge and - swearing off beer or - or all these other various dri
nks which after all are rather nice - I think is absurd. In fact whenever my wife and I - go out to lunch, if we got - she might have a bit of housekeeping money over, and - we generally have a drop of wine. I think it's very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 But your mother and father would never go to a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
My father never - now that was rather peculiar. During the Christmas holidays there was nothing for a - about three or four brothers and their wives to arrive do you see, from different places. Come down to Sheerness f
or a couple of day over the Christmas and Boxing Day. And then of course there was an awful problem of how they were going to sleep. But - the big problem was - how they were going to have - a little drop of beer in the house without - my mother or father
 
knowing. And that's - they used to work it - they used to work it that periodically one of them would be missing or his wife would be missing and they'd - go out and you'd say to yourself, I suppose they've gone in the back room. And - actually they'd gon
e
 in the back room to get a - have a glass of beer. But - I - I've got an idea - that - toward the end of my time anyhow that my father and mother knew that you know. I'm quite sure they did. But we had - used to have good fun, no doubt about that. Very ve
ry good fun indeed, all the old parlour games you know and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 This is Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Yes. Card games, all sitting round the table, about half a - oh, eight or nine perhaps. Playing donkey and old maid and - those sort of games. Good fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did your parents thing it was wrong to work or play on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. No, I don't think so, I don't say that - it was so universal - as it - to play on Sundays as it is now. But - I don't ever remember, mind you I - I wasn't allowed to kick a ball up and down
 the - back garden. But to play - play draughts for instance, wasn't a crime on a Sunday in any house. But - not by any means.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you ever have family prayers in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 No. No. No, we were never - I would say we were not - over religious fa
mily. My mother and father - always - saw that we had religious instruction. But - it was never - drummed into us or anything like that description. If we had religious instruction it was outside the home and in Sunday school or something like that. But h
aving done with that, well that was the end of the matter as far as they were concerned. No, I would say that my father and mother were damned good clean living people, and fairly broadminded I would say in those days. Oh yes, I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 What sort of 
people do you think they hoped their children would grow up to be the
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Well I wouldn't like to say that, I don't know, I - I do know this, that - although my mother - was very definitely anti-Socialist - I will say this, that she was rather proud of t
he fact that I was - a member of the Socialist party and I - occasionally got on the platform. She might have thought I was a damned fool but she was quite proud of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
What sort of values would you think that they emphasized as important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
I can - I would say truth really. I know they were very very keen indeed that I in particular, I'm only speaking about the effect on - myself, that I should never tell a lie. They were very very - keen on that, and I remember - telling an awful lie one 
day - we were always taught - to save money, not to spend it. That of course was another survival of the old days, of their days. And I had a money box, which was built in the shape of a little - post office, pillar box you know the round pillar boxes? Yo
u've probably seen the - money boxes have you? Well you put a - put the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361306\charrsid2252871 money}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  in the top and - you're all right. And - when Christmas comes you - you draw it all out again. And - that is then des - destroys the money box and you have another one for n
ext year. That's if your mother - and father - let you spend all the money. Usually the - next year is started off with about sixpence or a shilling from last year's money. And incidentally - I was rather adopt at - getting the money out. You probably kno
w
 the old dodge, you get a fairly broad knife - the pill - the little pillar box - is like that, the money - the slot goes that way. And you get a - a fairly broad knife, and you tip it up suddenly, and of course most of the money rests on the top of the k
n
ife. Well if you have a thin knife - and the pennies are fairly thin, by coming out with it very very gently you can draw some money out with it. And - I got fairly good at that. And - I do know this instance my mother and father were - rather worried, th
ey - I didn't seem to have any money in my - box do you see. In spite of the fact that people are always giving you money. And they asked me one day whether I took any out, and I said no. Oh there was a \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 about that. I don't know how they knew I h
ad but - they did know. They were right. And I remember my father saying - go upstairs, I'll come up presently. And when he came up - he gave me thas - thrashing, no doubt about that. And he said, I'm not - I'm not hitting you because - for taking the mon
