\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Did you see much of the policemen around when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 Well, policemen in those days were - almost friends of the family you kno
w. And in - living in a small town we knew all the policemen. Some of them were friends of my brothers do you see and they used to come to the house, that sort of thing. Which incidentally reminds me of a story - that one of my labourers told me. When I w
a
s in Farnborough. He was a - this fellow was a hulking great big bloke, and he'd been a policeman, in the Hants - Hampshire - police, and - he used to tell me some of his experiences when he brought my tea in in the morning. And - and if I had nothing on 
I
 used to sort of - draw him out. But anyhow he told me that one day - he was stationed in Farnborough, and - he said the Sergeant, we always knew when the Sergeant was coming. He said, he always said I'll meet you at so and so at such a time you see. He s
a
id, well - he said, I went home tell you the truth that night, he said, it was a rotten sort of night. He said, and - I - within about ten minutes of the time when the - Get into trouble, he said, so I went along to a field, and he mentioned the bloke's n
a
me by the way, one of the farmer lads, and - he said, I knew he had a horse in the - in the meadow, he says, so I opened the gate, went inside, chased this horse out and chased him along the road, he said, and - I - I drove him round to the part where the
 
- Sergeant was going to wait for me to meet him. He said, when I got there he said, he - he saw the horse, he said he saw me behind it. He said, you're late. I said, yes. So - so would you be with this bloody horse, he said, I've been chasing him all roun
d Farnborough, trying to get him back into his - into his field.
