\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Going back to your parents, one of the things you mentioned was when you went to the workshop, the dockyard, you learnt to swear. What did they think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 I don't ever remember that they - they heard me swear. I - I've often }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361306\charrsid2252871 marvelled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
 about this you know really. You hear more bad language now - among grown up people, outside works, than I ever heard when I was a kid. It almost seemed that in those days - when men took their o
veralls off - they entered into a new world. That their old habits - dirtiness, not caring about clothes, and not caring about their speech fell off them. Just as easily as taking their overalls off. And I never remember swearing in the - in our house, no
.
 In fact I'm more likely to swear now. Oh no, they - it's very very weird really. And with regard to - I mean, this - loose talk of sex and that sort of thing, do you know I never heard anything in my family with all my - brothers you know. Never. Most am
a
zing. I've known my brother, the partic - the sailor one who didn't care a damn whether it snowed - I know him to come home drunk, time after time, but I never heard him swear. Never heard him swear at all. In fact when he was drunk he was always very int
e
resting. In fact in the latter part of the time you know, I was - before I left home, before I was married - what would it be now, I suppose - eleven, twelve, thirteen and fourteen, he and I were pretty - particularly friendly because - he was nearly alwa
ys stationed in - Sheerness barracks. That was - one of the good turns that his older brother did for me really. And - and he and I were particularly friendly. And I learnt a lot from him. Even to - get drunk. But - nothing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361306\charrsid2252871 vicious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  about him at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 How did your mother and father react to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
My father was very annoyed. Very annoyed indeed. But my father wasn't quite - I was going to say he was - he wasn't fair to him. He probably was fair to him but - he was more annoyed than my mother. But you
 know - this idea of being drunk - unless you're a damned nuisance, it doesn't really matter a hell of a lot. I can remember - you probably have heard of Horatio Bottomley haven't you? Horrible scoundrel wasn't he. But anyhow, he - he had a publication ca
l
led John Bull. Remember that? On the front he had something about - the world is a bundle of hay, mankind are the asses who pull. Each pulls in a different way - but the greatest of all is John Bull. Right. Well - whenever my brother, this particular one,
 
was - tight - he always used to talk about Horatio Bottomley. And he always used to say to me, what we want is a business government. So after a time - it fell to my lot - to - when we thought he wasn't - coming home in a fit state, to wait up for him. An
d
 - incidentally we always knew when he was - going to get drunk. I'll tell you why. If he was going to get drunk, he would - always go out in his uniform. I - I used to marvel at that you know. But anyhow - to come back to the other point, and - the usual
 procedure was I used to sit up and wait for him you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361306\charrsid2252871 
'Cos my mother used to get ra - ra - rather worried my father had died by then, and - I used to sit and wait for him, and - I developed a sort of - a habit, not a habit - what shall I say - can't thi
nk of the damned word, but anyhow I knew precisely what I was going to do, put it that way. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
And - I would be reading in the kitchen, and - you would hear a scraping at the front door, with somebody trying to find the keyhole, and I wouldn't take the slight
est notice. And - after a time he would - put the key in and open - you know, open the door, close the door, not very softly, and stagger up the - passage. Come into the kitchen, and - I wouldn't take any notice at all. I'd still be - reading. Then after 
a
 time he'd say - well, aren't you going to say how do? Something like that you see. But if - if I had - said to him - hello old man. He'd say, what's the matter with you then? Don't you think I could get in? Or something, you know he would be - asking for
 
a quarrel actually. So right - so I didn't take any notice. But when he started to talk - I always used to judiciously lead the conversation into government. And within a couple of minutes, he would be in full flow. What Bottomley said and what Bottomley 
s
aid this and Bottomley said that and - I'll give you - I'll show you John Bull what it says and all this sort of thing. But anyhow in the meantime - the difficulty would be to get him to bed you see. So - I used to get up - say well now, I'm going to bed.
 
Cheerio, and I'd still be talking about John Bull, I'd light the candle, we always had candles in those days. I'd light the candle, I'd - turn out the gas in the kitchen, and I would walk up the passage with this candle with him following along behind ups
tairs, and we'd both go into the same bedroom, and he would get undressed, still talking about Bottomley, I would get undressed and he'd be all right.
