Yes. I would think so. They weren't - for instance my father always took me - to the football. And - he used to pay a penny for me to go in. Which was quite something. But he took me to the football and - he used
 to like to talk to me about football. You know, about the local team and all that sort of thing. It was very interesting. And I do know this, that he - he had one - very great ambition. He had an ambition that one day one of his sons would play for Sheff
i
eld United. And many years after that - when I was - making a bit of a name for myself at football - he did say to me one day, he said, well my boy, he said, I hope that you will - be what none of your elder brothers have been. I said, what's that? He sai
d, play for Sheppey United. Which I did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361306\charrsid2252871 incidentally}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
 but he never - he wasn't alive to see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 That would be about 1910 or so then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 That would be about eleven, twelve, thirteen, mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. No, not really. Occasionally - I was allowed to join in if - my people thought I was - what shall I say, had something - to contribute or some story to tell. They were rather - I - I think they were rather pleased at the fact that I had probably te
ll a tale, and - that - allowed me sometimes to speak, well that and - the greater amount of tolerance there was in - when I came along, from what there was when the others came along. I mean, that has to be borne in mind the whole time really. See lookin
g
 after one son or two sons like my elder brother, even he was five years older than me you know. With all the others out of the way, was quite a different proposition, and it could almost develop into a sort of a hobby, in those days. Which of course my e
lder brothers and sisters never had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4940319 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
Do you think that your mother and father were equally influential in bringing you up or was one more important than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5447395 SR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871 
No. I would say my mother - my mother was - in a way she was eloquent. Say - calle
d - call her fluent. She was certainly fluent, and - she was a woman of very very quick - I would say almost intuitions. You know, she never - she wouldn't think a problem out. She'd say, we'll do so and so. And as far as I can see - my father - if it was
n
't very important and if he didn't - think very very definitely and strongly the opposite, he would say OK my dear, that's all right. You see, fortunately in these - the effect of these little problems of hers didn't affect much. They weren't very - impor
tant. I do remember once - when my father - when we bought a house - when we - we moved out of Invicat Road into another house, and I well remember - my mother being very very annoyed at the fact - that the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361306\charrsid2252871 transference}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13846497\charrsid2252871  of the deeds had to be signed by my f
ather, and not her. I - I can distinctly remember her being very very annoyed and - in a childish sort of way, I didn't know what it was all about, but I did glean that - she was rather annoyed at the fact that this paper, these papers had to be left for 
